# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: stem-cell-biology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Scientific interest in adult stem cells is centered around two main characteristics.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] The first of which is their ability to divide or self-renew indefinitely, and the second their ability to generate all the cell types of the organ from which they originate, potentially regenerating the entire organ from a few cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Unlike embryonic stem cells, the use of human adult stem cells in research and therapy is not considered to be controversial, as they are derived from adult tissue samples rather than human embryos designated for scientific research.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] The main functions of adult stem cells are to replace cells that are at risk of possibly dying as a result of disease or injury and to maintain a state of homeostasis within the cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] There are three main methods to determine if the adult stem cell is capable of becoming a specialized cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] The adult stem cell can be labeled *in vivo* and tracked, it can be isolated and then transplanted back into the organism, and it can be isolated *in vivo* and manipulated with growth hormones.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] They have mainly been studied in humans and model organisms, such as mice, rats and planarians.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] To ensure self-renewal, stem cells undergo two types of cell division (see *Stem cell division and differentiation* diagram).
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Symmetric division gives rise to two identical daughter stem cells, whereas asymmetric division produces one stem cell and one progenitor cell with limited self-renewal potential.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Progenitors can go through several rounds of cell division before finally differentiating into a mature cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] It is believed that the molecular distinction between symmetric and asymmetric divisions lies in the differential segregation of cell membrane proteins (such as receptors) and their associated proteins between the daughter cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Under normal conditions, tissue stem cells divide slowly and infrequently.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] They exhibit signs of quiescence or reversible growth arrest.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] The niche the stem cell is found in plays a large role in maintaining quiescence.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Perturbed niches cause the stem cell to begin actively dividing again to replace lost or damaged cells until the niche is restored.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] In hematopoietic stem cells, the MAPK/ERK pathway and PI3K/AKT/mTOR pathway regulate this transition.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] The ability to regulate the cell cycle in response to external cues helps prevent stem cell exhaustion or the gradual loss of stem cells following an altered balance between dormant and active states.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Infrequent cell divisions also help reduce the risk of acquiring DNA mutations that would be passed on to daughter cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Discoveries in recent years have suggested that adult stem cells might have the ability to differentiate into cell types from different germ layers.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] For instance, neural stem cells from the brain, which are derived from ectoderm, can differentiate into ectoderm, mesoderm, and endoderm.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Stem cells from the bone marrow, which is derived from mesoderm, can differentiate into liver, lung, GI tract, and skin, which are derived from endoderm and mesoderm.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] This phenomenon is referred to as stem cell transdifferentiation or plasticity.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] It can be induced by modifying the growth medium when stem cells are cultured *in vitro* or by transplanting them to an organ of the body different from the one they were originally isolated from.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] There is yet no consensus among biologists on the prevalence and physiological and therapeutic relevance of stem cell plasticity.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] More recent findings suggest that pluripotent stem cells may reside in blood and adult tissues in a dormant state.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] These cells are referred to as "Blastomere Like Stem Cells" (BLSCs) and "very small embryonic-like" (VSEL) stem cells, and display pluripotency *in vitro*.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] As BLSCs and VSEL cells are present in virtually all adult tissues, including the lungs, brain, kidneys, muscles, and pancreas, co-purification of BLSCs and VSEL cells with other populations of adult stem cells may explain the apparent pluripotency of adult stem cell populations.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] However, recent studies have shown that both human and murine VSEL cells lack stem cell characteristics and are not pluripotent.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Stem cell function becomes impaired with age, and this contributes to progressive deterioration of tissue maintenance and repair.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] A likely important cause of increasing stem cell dysfunction is an age-dependent accumulation of DNA damage in both stem cells and the cells that comprise the stem cell environment.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Adult stem cells can, however, be artificially reverted to a state where they behave like embryonic stem cells (including the associated DNA repair mechanisms).
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] This was done with mice as early as 2006 with prospects to slow down human aging substantially.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Such cells are one of the various classes of induced stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Adult stem cell research has been focused on uncovering the general molecular mechanisms that control their self-renewal and differentiation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] has been known to developmental biologists for decades.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] These developmental pathways are also strongly implicated as stem cell regulators.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Hematopoietic stem cells (HSCs) are stem cells that can differentiate into all blood cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Hematopoietic stem cells are found in the bone marrow and umbilical cord blood.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] The HSCs are generally dormant when found in adults due to their nature.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Mammary stem cells provide the source of cells for the growth of the mammary gland during puberty and gestation and play an important role in the carcinogenesis of the breast.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Mammary stem cells have been isolated from human and mouse tissue as well as from cell lines derived from the mammary gland.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Single such cells can give rise to both the luminal and myoepithelial cell types of the gland and have been shown to have the ability to regenerate the entire organ in mice.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Intestinal stem cells divide continuously throughout life and use a complex genetic program to produce the cells lining the surface of the small and large intestines.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Intestinal stem cells reside near the base of the stem cell niche, called the crypts of Lieberkuhn.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Intestinal stem cells are probably the source of most cancers of the small intestine and colon.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs) are of stromal origin and may differentiate into a variety of tissues.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] MSCs have been isolated from the placenta, adipose tissue, lung, bone marrow and blood, Wharton's jelly from the umbilical cord, and teeth (perivascular niche of dental pulp and periodontal ligament).
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] MSCs are attractive for clinical therapy due to their ability to differentiate, provide trophic support, and modulate innate immune response.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] These cells differentiate into various cell types such as osteoblasts, chondroblasts, adipocytes, neuroectodermal cells, and hepatocytes.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Bioactive mediators that favor local cell growth are also secreted by MSCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Anti-inflammatory effects on the local microenvironment, which promote tissue healing, are also observed.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] The inflammatory response can be modulated by adipose-derived regenerative cells (ADRC) including mesenchymal stem cells and regulatory T-lymphocytes.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] The mesenchymal stem cells thus alter the outcome of the immune response by changing the cytokine secretion of dendritic and T-cell subsets.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] This results in a shift from a pro-inflammatory environment to an anti-inflammatory or tolerant cell environment.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Endothelial stem cells are one of the three types of multipotent stem cells found in the bone marrow.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] They are a rare and controversial group with the ability to differentiate into endothelial cells, the cells that line blood vessels as well as lymphatic vessels.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Endothelial stem cells are an important aspect of the vascular network, even influencing the motion relating to white blood cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] The existence of stem cells in the adult brain has been postulated following the discovery that the process of neurogenesis, the birth of new neurons, continues into adulthood in rats.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] The presence of stem cells in the mature primate brain was first reported in 1967.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] It has since been shown that new neurons are generated in adult mice, songbirds, and primates, including humans.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Normally, adult neurogenesis is restricted to two areas of the brain – the subventricular zone, which lines the lateral ventricles, and the dentate gyrus of the hippocampal formation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Although the generation of new neurons in the hippocampus is well established, the presence of true self-renewing stem cells there has been debated.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Under certain circumstances, such as following tissue damage in ischemia, neurogenesis can be induced in other brain regions, including the neocortex.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Neural stem cells are commonly cultured *in vitro* as so-called neurospheres – floating heterogeneous aggregates of cells, containing a large proportion of stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] They can be propagated for extended periods and differentiated into both neuronal and glial cells, and therefore behave as stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] However, some recent studies suggest that this behavior is induced by the culture conditions in progenitor cells, the progeny of stem cell division that normally undergo a strictly limited number of replication cycles *in vivo*.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Furthermore, neurosphere-derived cells do not behave as stem cells when transplanted back into the brain.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Neural stem cells share many properties with hematopoietic stem cells (HSCs).
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Remarkably, when injected into the blood, neurosphere-derived cells differentiate into various cell types of the immune system.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Olfactory adult stem cells have been successfully harvested from the human olfactory mucosa cells, which are found in the lining of the nose and are involved in the sense of smell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] If they are given the right chemical environment, these cells have the same ability as embryonic stem cells to develop into many different cell types.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Olfactory stem cells hold the potential for therapeutic applications and, in contrast to neural stem cells, can be harvested with ease without harm to the patient.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] This means they can be easily obtained from all individuals, including older patients who might be most in need of stem cell therapies.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Hair follicles contain two types of stem cells, one of which appears to represent a remnant of the stem cells of the embryonic neural crest.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Similar cells have been found in the gastrointestinal tract, sciatic nerve, cardiac outflow tract and spinal and sympathetic ganglia.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] These cells can generate neurons, Schwann cells, myofibroblasts, chondrocytes, and melanocytes.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Multipotent stem cells have also been derived from germ cells found in human testicles.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Adult stem cell treatments have been used for many years to successfully treat leukemia and related bone/blood cancers utilizing bone marrow transplants.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] The use of adult stem cells in research and therapy is not considered as controversial as the use of embryonic stem cells, because the production of adult stem cells does not require the destruction of an embryo.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Early regenerative applications of adult stem cells have focused on intravenous delivery of blood progenitors known as Hematopoietic Stem Cells (HSCs).
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] CD34+ hematopoietic Stem Cells have been clinically applied to treat various diseases including spinal cord injury, liver cirrhosis and Peripheral Vascular disease.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Research has shown that CD34+ hematopoietic Stem Cells are relatively more numerous in men than in women of reproductive age group among spinal cord Injury victims.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Other early commercial applications have focused on Mesenchymal Stem Cells (MSCs).
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] For both cell lines, direct injection or placement of cells into a site in need of repair may be the preferred method of treatment, as vascular delivery suffers from a "pulmonary first pass effect" where intravenously injected cells are sequestered in the lungs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Clinical case reports in orthopedic applications have been published.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Wakitani has published a small case series of nine defects in five knees involving surgical transplantation of mesenchymal stem cells with coverage of the treated chondral defects.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Centeno et al. have reported high-field MRI evidence of increased cartilage and meniscus volume in individual human clinical subjects as well as a large n=227 safety study.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Many other stem cell-based treatments are operating outside the US, with much controversy being reported regarding these treatments as some feel more regulation is needed as clinics tend to exaggerate claims of success and minimize or omit risks.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] The therapeutic potential of adult stem cells is the focus of much scientific research, due to their ability to be harvested from the parent body that is females during the delivery.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] In common with embryonic stem cells, adult stem cells can differentiate into more than one cell type, but unlike the former they are often restricted to certain types or "lineages".
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] The ability of a differentiated stem cell of one lineage to produce cells of a different lineage is called transdifferentiation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Some types of adult stem cells are more capable of transdifferentiation than others, but for many there is no evidence that such a transformation is possible.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Consequently, adult stem therapies require a stem cell source of the specific lineage needed, and harvesting and/or culturing them up to the numbers required is a challenge.
[src:stem-cell-biology/adult-stem-cell] Additionally, cues from the immediate environment (including how stiff or porous the surrounding structure/extracellular matrix is) can alter or enhance the fate and differentiation of the stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Totipotency (Latin: *totipotentia*, lit.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] 'ability for all [things]') is the ability of a single cell to divide and produce all of the differentiated cells in an organism.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Spores and zygotes are examples of totipotent cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] In the spectrum of cell potency, totipotency represents the cell with the greatest differentiation potential, being able to differentiate into any embryonic cell, as well as any extraembryonic tissue cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] In contrast, pluripotent cells can only differentiate into embryonic cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] A fully differentiated cell can return to a state of totipotency.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] The conversion to totipotency is complex and not fully understood.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] In 2011, research revealed that cells may differentiate not into a fully totipotent cell, but instead into a "complex cellular variation" of totipotency.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] The human development model can be used to describe how totipotent cells arise.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Human development begins when a sperm fertilizes an egg, and the resulting fertilized egg creates a single totipotent cell, a zygote.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] In the first hours after fertilization, this zygote divides into identical totipotent cells, which can later develop into any of the three germ layers of a human (endoderm, mesoderm, or ectoderm), or into cells of the placenta (cytotrophoblast or syncytiotrophoblast).
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] After reaching a 16-cell stage, the totipotent cells of the morula differentiate into cells that will eventually become either the blastocyst's inner cell mass or the outer trophoblasts.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Approximately four days after fertilization, and after several cycles of cell division, these totipotent cells begin to specialize.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] The inner cell mass, the source of embryonic stem cells, becomes pluripotent.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Research on *Caenorhabditis elegans* suggests that multiple mechanisms, including RNA regulation, may play a role in maintaining totipotency at different stages of development in some species.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Work with zebrafish and mammals suggest a further interplay between miRNA and RNA-binding proteins (RBPs) in determining development differences.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] In mouse primordial germ cells, genome-wide reprogramming leading to totipotency involves erasure of epigenetic imprints.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Reprogramming is facilitated by active DNA demethylation involving the DNA base excision repair enzymatic pathway.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] This pathway entails erasure of CpG methylation (5mC) in primordial germ cells via the initial conversion of 5mC to 5-hydroxymethylcytosine (5hmC), a reaction driven by high levels of the ten-eleven dioxygenase enzymes TET-1 and TET-2.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] A pluripotent stem cell (Latin: *pluripotentia*, lit.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Induced pluripotent stem cells, commonly abbreviated as iPS cells or iPSCs, are a type of pluripotent stem cell artificially derived from a non-pluripotent cell, typically an adult somatic cell, by inducing a "forced" expression of certain genes and transcription factors.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] These transcription factors play a key role in determining the state of these cells and also highlights the fact that these somatic cells do preserve the same genetic information as early embryonic cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] The ability to induce cells into a pluripotent state was initially pioneered in 2006 using mouse fibroblasts and four transcription factors, Oct4, Sox2, Klf4 and c-Myc; this technique, called reprogramming, later earned Shinya Yamanaka and John Gurdon the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] This was then followed in 2007 by the successful induction of human iPSCs derived from human dermal fibroblasts using methods similar to those used for the induction of mouse cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] These induced cells exhibit similar traits to those of embryonic stem cells (ESCs) but do not require the use of embryos.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Some of the similarities between ESCs and iPSCs include pluripotency, morphology, self-renewal ability, a trait that implies that they can divide and replicate indefinitely, and gene expression.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Epigenetic factors are also thought to be involved in the actual reprogramming of somatic cells in order to induce pluripotency.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] It has been theorized that certain epigenetic factors might actually work to clear the original somatic epigenetic marks in order to acquire the new epigenetic marks that are part of achieving a pluripotent state.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Chromatin is also reorganized in iPSCs and becomes like that found in ESCs in that it is less condensed and therefore more accessible.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Euchromatin modifications are also common which is also consistent with the state of euchromatin found in ESCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Due to their great similarity to ESCs, the medical and research communities are interested in iPSCs. iPSCs could potentially have the same therapeutic implications and applications as ESCs but without the controversial use of embryos in the process, a topic of great bioethical debate.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] The induced pluripotency of somatic cells into undifferentiated iPS cells was originally hailed as the end of the controversial use of embryonic stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] However, iPSCs were found to be potentially tumorigenic, and, despite advances, were never approved for clinical stage research in the United States until recently.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Currently, autologous iPSC-derived dopaminergic progenitor cells are used in trials for treating Parkinson's disease.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Setbacks such as low replication rates and early senescence have also been encountered when making iPSCs, hindering their use as ESCs replacements.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] This result challenges the terminal nature of cellular differentiation and the integrity of lineage commitment; and implies that with the proper tools, *all* cells are totipotent and may form all kinds of tissue.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] As the continued research and application of ESCs and iPSCs expands in regenerative medicine models, quality checks of test cells are needed.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] A widely accepted procedure that works for both mammalian ESCs and iPSCs is the teratoma formation assay.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] A teratoma is a benign (typically) tumor that is characterized by its ability to form the three germ layers: ectoderm (nerves, epithelium), mesoderm (muscle, bone, and cartilage), and endoderm (gut).
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] A teratoma formation assay is done by injecting test cells that are expected pluripotent cells into various tissues.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] A few areas include but are not limited to: the kidney capsule, intra-testicular, and intramuscular regions of mice that are immune-deficient.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Determined pluripotency is characterized by the test cell's ability to form a teratoma that is capable of producing the three distinct germ layers.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] While the teratoma formation assay is considered the "gold standard" among researchers, many issues have arisen with the test.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] One particular issue is the lack of standardization regarding specific details and factors that influence teratoma formation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Areas of concern for standardization are graft sites, age of test organism (typically mice), and the number of cells being injected into the test organism.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] These assays are also costly and operationally burdensome, and ethical concerns are an issue due to the use of test organisms.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Another issue with this type of testing is the possibility of histological reading errors.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Cells that are not completely reprogrammed into iPSCs that form noticeable cell masses, which look similar characteristically to teratomas, may be judged as pluripotent while lacking the three germ layers.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] The need for tracking of cell lineages and host versus donor cell markings has also been noted.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Certain cell preparation materials may induce an inflammatory response or a foreign antigen immune response.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] These responses may play a role in falsely identifying differentiation of the test cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Findings with respect to epiblasts before and after implantation have produced proposals for classifying pluripotency into two states: "naive" and "primed", representing pre- and post-implantation epiblast, respectively.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Naive-to-primed continuum is controlled by reduction of Sox2/Oct4 dimerization on SoxOct DNA elements controlling naive pluripotency.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Primed pluripotent stem cells from different species could be reset to naive state using a cocktail containing Klf4 and Sox2 or "super-Sox" − a chimeric transcription factor with enhanced capacity to dimerize with Oct4.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] The baseline stem cells commonly used in science that are referred as embryonic stem cells (ESCs) are derived from a pre-implantation epiblast; such epiblast is able to generate the entire fetus, and one epiblast cell is able to contribute to all cell lineages if injected into another blastocyst.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] During this development, the egg cylinder epiblast cells are systematically targeted by Fibroblast growth factors, Wnt signaling, and other inductive factors via the surrounding yolk sac and the trophoblast tissue, such that they become instructively specific according to the spatial organization.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Another major difference is that post-implantation epiblast stem cells are unable to contribute to blastocyst chimeras, which distinguishes them from other known pluripotent stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Cell lines derived from such post-implantation epiblasts are referred to as epiblast-derived stem cells, which were first derived in laboratory in 2007.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Both ESCs and EpiSCs are derived from epiblasts but at difference phases of development.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Pluripotency is still intact in the post-implantation epiblast, as demonstrated by the conserved expression of Nanog, Fut4, and Oct-4 in EpiSCs, until somitogenesis and can be reversed midway through induced expression of Oct-4.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Un-induced pluripotency has been observed in root meristem tissue culture, especially by Kareem et al 2015, Kim et al 2018, and Rosspopoff et al 2017.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] This pluripotency is regulated by various regulators, including PLETHORA 1 and PLETHORA 2; and PLETHORA 3, PLETHORA 5, and PLETHORA 7, whose expression were found by Kareem to be auxin-provoked.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] (These are also known as PLT1, PLT2, PLT3, PLT5, PLT7, and expressed by genes of the same names.) As of 2019, this is expected to open up future research into pluripotency in root tissues.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] The maintenance of the pluripotency state relies on a finely balanced network of transcription factors, signaling pathways, and epigenetic regulators that work together to preserve a cell’s capacity for unlimited self-renewal and its potential to differentiate into all cell types.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Core transcription factors such as OCT4, SOX2, and NANOG form the central regulatory circuitry that sustains pluripotency by activating genes essential for self-renewal while repressing differentiation signals.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Multipotency is when progenitor cells have the gene activation potential to differentiate into discrete cell types.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] For example, a hematopoietic stem cell – and this cell type can differentiate itself into several types of blood cell like lymphocytes, monocytes, neutrophils, etc., but it is still ambiguous whether HSC possess the ability to differentiate into brain cells, bone cells or other non-blood cell types.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Research related to multipotent cells suggests that multipotent cells may be capable of conversion into unrelated cell types.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] In another case, human umbilical cord blood stem cells were converted into human neurons.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] There is also research on converting multipotent cells into pluripotent cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Multipotent cells are found in many, but not all human cell types.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Multipotent cells have been found in cord blood, adipose tissue, cardiac cells, bone marrow, and mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs) which are found in the third molar.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] MSCs may prove to be a valuable source for stem cells from molars at 8–10 years of age, before adult dental calcification.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] MSCs can differentiate into osteoblasts, chondrocytes, and adipocytes.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] In biology, oligopotency is the ability of progenitor cells to differentiate into a few cell types.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Examples of oligopotent stem cells are the lymphoid or myeloid stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] A lymphoid cell specifically, can give rise to various blood cells such as B and T cells, however, not to a different blood cell type like a red blood cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Examples of progenitor cells are vascular stem cells that have the capacity to become both endothelial or smooth muscle cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] A unipotent cell is a stem cell that has the capacity to differentiate into only one cell type.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Unlike pluripotent or multipotent stem cells, which can become many different kinds of cells, unipotent cells can only produce a single mature cell type.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Despite this limited differentiation potential, they often have the ability to self-renew, which means they can make more copies of themselves.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Unipotent cells are often referred to as precursor cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] However, the classification of truly unipotent stem cells remains a subject of scientific discussion.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Some cells previously labeled as unipotent may instead be progenitor cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Progenitor cells are cells that are already committed to a specific developmental pathway and do not have a long-term self-renewal ability.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] This distinction is important because true stem cells must be able to both differentiate and maintain their population over time.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] As a result, determination of a true unipotent cell can be challenging.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] For example, hepatoblasts were once thought to be unipotent.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] Instead, they are bipotent because they can differentiate into hepatocytes or cholangiocytes**.** This example highlights how advances in experimental evidence can refine how cell types are classified.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] In cell biology, a nullipotent cell is one that does not have a capacity to differentiate into any other cell type (Latin: *nullipotentia*, lit.
[src:stem-cell-biology/cell-potency] While the term can be used to describe terminally differentiated cells (such as neurons, red blood cells, etc.) it is most commonly used when referring to embryonal carcinoma (EC) or embryonic stem cells that have lost their differentiation ability (usually due to genetic mutations).
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Researchers focus heavily on the therapeutic potential of embryonic stem cells, with clinical use being the goal for many laboratories.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Potential uses include the treatment of diabetes and heart disease.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The cells are studied to be used as clinical therapies, models of genetic disorders, and cellular/DNA repair.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] However, adverse effects in the research and clinical processes such as tumors and unwanted immune responses have also been reported.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Embryonic stem cells (ESCs), derived from the blastocyst stage of early mammalian embryos, are distinguished by their ability to differentiate into any embryonic cell type and by their ability to self-renew.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] It is these traits that makes them valuable in the scientific and medical fields.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] ESCs have a normal karyotype, maintain high telomerase activity, and exhibit remarkable long-term proliferative potential.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Embryonic stem cells of the inner cell mass are pluripotent, meaning they are able to differentiate to generate primitive ectoderm, which ultimately differentiates during gastrulation into all derivatives of the three primary germ layers: ectoderm, endoderm, and mesoderm.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] These germ layers generate each of the more than 220 cell types in the adult human body.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] When provided with the appropriate signals, ESCs initially form precursor cells that in subsequently differentiate into the desired cell types.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Pluripotency distinguishes embryonic stem cells from adult stem cells, which are multipotent and can only produce a limited number of cell types.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Under defined conditions, embryonic stem cells are capable of self-renewing indefinitely in an undifferentiated state.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Self-renewal conditions must prevent the cells from clumping and maintain an environment that supports an unspecialized state.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Typically this is done in the lab with media containing serum and leukemia inhibitory factor or serum-free media supplements with two inhibitory drugs ("2i"), the MEK inhibitor PD03259010 and GSK-3 inhibitor CHIR99021.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] ESCs divide very frequently due to a shortened G1 phase in their cell cycle.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Rapid cell division allows the cells to quickly grow in number, but not size, which is important for early embryo development.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] In ESCs, cyclin A and cyclin E proteins involved in the G1/S transition are always expressed at high levels.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Cyclin-dependent kinases such as CDK2 that promote cell cycle progression are overactive, in part due to downregulation of their inhibitors.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Retinoblastoma proteins that inhibit the transcription factor E2F until the cell is ready to enter S phase are hyperphosphorylated and inactivated in ESCs, leading to continual expression of proliferation genes.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] These changes result in accelerated cycles of cell division.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Although high expression levels of pro-proliferative proteins and a shortened G1 phase have been linked to maintenance of pluripotency, ESCs grown in serum-free 2i conditions do express hypo-phosphorylated active Retinoblastoma proteins and have an elongated G1 phase.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Despite this difference in the cell cycle when compared to ESCs grown in media containing serum these cells have similar pluripotent characteristics.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Pluripotency factors Oct4 and Nanog play a role in transcriptionally regulating the embryonic stem cell cycle.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Due to their plasticity and potentially unlimited capacity for self-renewal, embryonic stem cell therapies have been proposed for regenerative medicine and tissue replacement after injury or disease.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Pluripotent stem cells have shown promise in treating a number of varying conditions, including but not limited to: spinal cord injuries, age related macular degeneration, diabetes, neurodegenerative disorders (such as Parkinson's disease), AIDS, etc.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] In addition to their potential in regenerative medicine, embryonic stem cells provide a possible alternative source of tissue/organs which serves as a possible solution to the donor shortage dilemma.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] However, there are ethical controversies surrounding this (see **Ethical debate** section below).
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Aside from these uses, ESCs can also be used for research on early human development, certain genetic disease, and *in vitro* toxicology testing.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] In tissue engineering, the use of stem cells are known to be of importance.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] In order to successfully engineer a tissue, the cells used must be able to perform specific biological functions such as secretion of cytokines, signaling molecules, interacting with neighboring cells, and producing an extracellular matrix in the correct organization.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Stem cells demonstrates these specific biological functions along with being able to self-renew and differentiate into one or more types of specialized cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Embryonic stem cells is one of the sources that are being considered for the use of tissue engineering.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The use of human embryonic stem cells have opened many new possibilities for tissue engineering, however, there are many hurdles that must be made before human embryonic stem cell can even be utilized.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] It is theorized that if embryonic stem cells can be altered to not evoke the immune response when implanted into the patient then this would be a revolutionary step in tissue engineering.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Embryonic stem cells are not limited to tissue engineering.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Research has focused on differentiating ESCs into a variety of cell types for eventual use as cell replacement therapies.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Some of the cell types that have or are currently being developed include cardiomyocytes, neurons, hepatocytes, bone marrow cells, islet cells and endothelial cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] However, the derivation of such cell types from ESCs is not without obstacles, therefore research has focused on overcoming these barriers.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] For example, studies are underway to differentiate ESCs into tissue specific cardiomyocytes and to eradicate their immature properties that distinguish them from adult cardiomyocytes.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Besides becoming an important alternative to organ transplants, ESCs are also being used in the field of toxicology, and as cellular screens to uncover new chemical entities that can be developed as small-molecule drugs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Studies have shown that cardiomyocytes derived from ESCs are validated *in vitro* models to test drug responses and predict toxicity profiles.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] ESC derived cardiomyocytes have been shown to respond to pharmacological stimuli and hence can be used to assess cardiotoxicity such as torsades de pointes.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] ESC-derived hepatocytes are also useful models that could be used in the preclinical stages of drug discovery.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] However, the development of hepatocytes from ESCs has proven to be challenging and this hinders the ability to test drug metabolism.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Therefore, research has focused on establishing fully functional ESC-derived hepatocytes with stable phase I and II enzyme activity.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Several new studies have started to address the concept of modeling genetic disorders with embryonic stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Either by genetically manipulating the cells, or more recently, by deriving diseased cell lines identified by prenatal genetic diagnosis (PGD), modeling genetic disorders is something that has been accomplished with stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] This approach may very well prove valuable at studying disorders such as Fragile-X syndrome, Cystic fibrosis, and other genetic maladies that have no reliable model system.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Yury Verlinsky, a Russian-American medical researcher who specialized in embryo and cellular genetics (genetic cytology), developed prenatal diagnosis testing methods to determine genetic and chromosomal disorders a month and a half earlier than standard amniocentesis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The techniques are now used by many pregnant women and prospective parents, especially couples who have a history of genetic abnormalities or where the woman is over the age of 35 (when the risk of genetically related disorders is higher).
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] In addition, by allowing parents to select an embryo without genetic disorders, they have the potential of saving the lives of siblings that already had similar disorders and diseases using cells from the disease free offspring.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Differentiated somatic cells and ES cells use different strategies for dealing with DNA damage.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] For instance, human foreskin fibroblasts, one type of somatic cell, use non-homologous end joining (NHEJ), an error prone DNA repair process, as the primary pathway for repairing double-strand breaks (DSBs) during all cell cycle stages.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Because of its error-prone nature, NHEJ tends to produce mutations in a cell's clonal descendants.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] ES cells use a different strategy to deal with DSBs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Because ES cells give rise to all of the cell types of an organism including the cells of the germ line, mutations arising in ES cells due to faulty DNA repair are a more serious problem than in differentiated somatic cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Consequently, robust mechanisms are needed in ES cells to repair DNA damages accurately, and if repair fails, to remove those cells with un-repaired DNA damages.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Thus, mouse ES cells predominantly use high fidelity homologous recombinational repair (HRR) to repair DSBs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] This type of repair depends on the interaction of the two sister chromosomes formed during S phase and present together during the G2 phase of the cell cycle.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] HRR can accurately repair DSBs in one sister chromosome by using intact information from the other sister chromosome.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Cells in the G1 phase of the cell cycle (i.e. after metaphase/cell division but prior the next round of replication) have only one copy of each chromosome (i.e. sister chromosomes aren't present).
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Mouse ES cells lack a G1 checkpoint and do not undergo cell cycle arrest upon acquiring DNA damage.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Rather they undergo programmed cell death (apoptosis) in response to DNA damage.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Apoptosis can be used as a fail-safe strategy to remove cells with un-repaired DNA damages in order to avoid mutation and progression to cancer.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Consistent with this strategy, mouse ES stem cells have a mutation frequency about 100-fold lower than that of isogenic mouse somatic cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] On January 23, 2009, Phase I clinical trials for transplantation of oligodendrocytes (a cell type of the brain and spinal cord) derived from human ESCs into spinal cord-injured individuals received approval from the U.S.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Food and Drug Administration (FDA), marking it the world's first human ESC human trial.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The study leading to this scientific advancement was conducted by Hans Keirstead and colleagues at the University of California, Irvine and supported by Geron Corporation of Menlo Park, CA, founded by Michael D.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] A previous experiment had shown an improvement in locomotor recovery in spinal cord-injured rats after a 7-day delayed transplantation of human ESCs that had been pushed into an oligodendrocytic lineage.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The phase I clinical study was designed to enroll about eight to ten paraplegics who have had their injuries no longer than two weeks before the trial begins, since the cells must be injected before scar tissue is able to form.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The researchers emphasized that the injections were not expected to fully cure the patients and restore all mobility.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Based on the results of the rodent trials, researchers speculated that restoration of myelin sheathes and an increase in mobility might occur.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] This first trial was primarily designed to test the safety of these procedures and if everything went well, it was hoped that it would lead to future studies that involve people with more severe disabilities.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The trial was put on hold in August 2009 due to FDA concerns regarding a small number of microscopic cysts found in several treated rat models but the hold was lifted on July 30, 2010.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] In October 2010 researchers enrolled and administered ESCs to the first patient at Shepherd Center in Atlanta.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The makers of the stem cell therapy, Geron Corporation, estimated that it would take several months for the stem cells to replicate and for the GRNOPC1 therapy to be evaluated for success or failure.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] In November 2011 Geron announced it was halting the trial and dropping out of stem cell research for financial reasons, but would continue to monitor existing patients, and was attempting to find a partner that could continue their research.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] West, acquired all of Geron's stem cell assets, with the stated intention of restarting Geron's embryonic stem cell-based clinical trial for spinal cord injury research.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] BioTime company Asterias Biotherapeutics (NYSE MKT: AST) was granted a $14.3 million Strategic Partnership Award by the California Institute for Regenerative Medicine (CIRM) to re-initiate the world's first embryonic stem cell-based human clinical trial, for spinal cord injury.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Supported by California public funds, CIRM is the largest funder of stem cell-related research and development in the world.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The award provides funding for Asterias to reinitiate clinical development of AST-OPC1 in subjects with spinal cord injury and to expand clinical testing of escalating doses in the target population intended for future pivotal trials.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] AST-OPC1 is a population of cells derived from human embryonic stem cells (hESCs) that contains oligodendrocyte progenitor cells (OPCs).
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] OPCs and their mature derivatives called oligodendrocytes provide critical functional support for nerve cells in the spinal cord and brain.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Asterias recently presented the results from phase 1 clinical trial testing of a low dose of AST-OPC1 in patients with neurologically complete thoracic spinal cord injury.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The results showed that AST-OPC1 was successfully delivered to the injured spinal cord site.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Patients followed 2–3 years after AST-OPC1 administration showed no evidence of serious adverse events associated with the cells in detailed follow-up assessments including frequent neurological exams and MRIs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Immune monitoring of subjects through one year post-transplantation showed no evidence of antibody-based or cellular immune responses to AST-OPC1.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] In four of the five subjects, serial MRI scans performed throughout the 2–3 year follow-up period indicate that reduced spinal cord cavitation may have occurred and that AST-OPC1 may have had some positive effects in reducing spinal cord tissue deterioration.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] There was no unexpected neurological degeneration or improvement in the five subjects in the trial as evaluated by the International Standards for Neurological Classification of Spinal Cord Injury (ISNCSCI) exam.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] CIRM funding will be conditional on FDA approval for the trial, completion of a definitive agreement between Asterias and CIRM, and Asterias' continued progress toward the achievement of certain pre-defined project milestones.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The major concern with the possible transplantation of ESCs into patients as therapies is their ability to form tumors including teratomas.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Safety issues prompted the FDA to place a hold on the first ESC clinical trial, however no tumors were observed.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The main strategy to enhance the safety of ESCs for potential clinical use is to differentiate the ESCs into specific cell types (e.g. neurons, muscle, liver cells) that have reduced or eliminated ability to cause tumors.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Following differentiation, the cells are subjected to sorting by flow cytometry for further purification.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] ESCs are predicted to be inherently safer than iPS cells created with genetically integrating viral vectors because they are not genetically modified with genes such as c-Myc that are linked to cancer.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Nonetheless, ESCs express very high levels of the iPS inducing genes and these genes including Myc are essential for ESC self-renewal and pluripotency, and potential strategies to improve safety by eliminating c-Myc expression are unlikely to preserve the cells' "stemness".
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] However, N-myc and L-myc have been identified to induce iPS cells instead of c-myc with similar efficiency.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Later protocols to induce pluripotency bypass these problems completely by using non-integrating RNA viral vectors such as sendai virus or mRNA transfection.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Due to the nature of embryonic stem cell research, there are a lot of controversial opinions on the topic.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Since harvesting embryonic stem cells usually necessitates destroying the embryo from which those cells are obtained, the moral status of the embryo comes into question.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Some people claim that the embryo is too young to achieve personhood or that the embryo, if donated from an IVF clinic (where labs typically acquire embryos), would otherwise go to medical waste anyway.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Opponents of ESC research claim that an embryo is a human life, therefore destroying it is murder and the embryo must be protected under the same ethical view as a more developed human being.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] In vitro fertilization generates multiple embryos.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The surplus of embryos is not clinically used or is unsuitable for implantation into the patient, and therefore may be donated by the donor with consent.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Human embryonic stem cells can be derived from these donated embryos or additionally they can also be extracted from cloned embryos created using a cell from a patient and a donated egg through the process of somatic cell nuclear transfer.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The inner cell mass (cells of interest), from the blastocyst stage of the embryo, is separated from the trophectoderm, the cells that would differentiate into extra-embryonic tissue.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Immunosurgery, the process in which antibodies are bound to the trophectoderm and removed by another solution, and mechanical dissection are performed to achieve separation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The resulting inner cell mass cells are plated onto cells that will supply support.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The inner cell mass cells attach and expand further to form a human embryonic cell line, which are undifferentiated.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] These cells are fed daily and are enzymatically or mechanically separated every four to seven days.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] For differentiation to occur, the human embryonic stem cell line is removed from the supporting cells to form embryoid bodies, is co-cultured with a serum containing necessary signals, or is grafted in a three-dimensional scaffold to result.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Embryonic stem cells are derived from the inner cell mass of the early embryo, which are harvested from the donor mother animal.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Martin Evans and Matthew Kaufman reported a technique that delays embryo implantation, allowing the inner cell mass to increase.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] This process includes removing the donor mother's ovaries and dosing her with progesterone, changing the hormone environment, which causes the embryos to remain free in the uterus.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] After 4–6 days of this intrauterine culture, the embryos are harvested and grown in *in vitro* culture until the inner cell mass forms "egg cylinder-like structures," which are dissociated into single cells, and plated on fibroblasts treated with mitomycin-c (to prevent fibroblast mitosis).
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Clonal cell lines are created by growing up a single cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Evans and Kaufman showed that the cells grown out from these cultures could form teratomas and embryoid bodies, and differentiate *in vitro,* all of which indicating that the cells are pluripotent.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Gail Martin derived and cultured her ES cells differently.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] She removed the embryos from the donor mother at approximately 76 hours after copulation and cultured them overnight in a medium containing serum.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The following day, she removed the inner cell mass from the late blastocyst using microsurgery.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The extracted inner cell mass was cultured on fibroblasts treated with mitomycin-c in a medium containing serum and conditioned by ES cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] After approximately one week, colonies of cells grew out.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] These cells grew in culture and demonstrated pluripotent characteristics, as demonstrated by the ability to form teratomas, differentiate *in vitro,* and form embryoid bodies.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Martin referred to these cells as ES cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] It is now known that the feeder cells provide leukemia inhibitory factor (LIF) and serum provides bone morphogenetic proteins (BMPs) that are necessary to prevent ES cells from differentiating.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] These factors are extremely important for the efficiency of deriving ES cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Furthermore, it has been demonstrated that different mouse strains have different efficiencies for isolating ES cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Current uses for mouse ES cells include the generation of transgenic mice, including knockout mice.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] For human treatment, there is a need for patient specific pluripotent cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Generation of human ES cells is more difficult and faces ethical issues.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] So, in addition to human ES cell research, many groups are focused on the generation of induced pluripotent stem cells (iPS cells).
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] On August 23, 2006, the online edition of *Nature* scientific journal published a letter by Dr.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Robert Lanza (medical director of Advanced Cell Technology in Worcester, MA) stating that his team had found a way to extract embryonic stem cells without destroying the actual embryo.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] This technical achievement would potentially enable scientists to work with new lines of embryonic stem cells derived using public funding in the US, where federal funding was at the time limited to research using embryonic stem cell lines derived prior to August 2001.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] In March, 2009, the limitation was lifted.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Human embryonic stem cells have also been derived by somatic cell nuclear transfer (SCNT).
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] This approach has also sometimes been referred to as "therapeutic cloning" because SCNT bears similarity to other kinds of cloning in that nuclei are transferred from a somatic cell into an enucleated zygote.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] However, in this case SCNT was used to produce embryonic stem cell lines in a lab, not living organisms via a pregnancy.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The "therapeutic" part of the name is included because of the hope that SCNT produced embryonic stem cells could have clinical utility.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The iPS cell technology was pioneered by Shinya Yamanaka's lab in Kyoto, Japan, who showed in 2006 that the introduction of four specific genes encoding transcription factors could convert adult cells into pluripotent stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] In 2007, it was shown that pluripotent stem cells, highly similar to embryonic stem cells, can be induced by the delivery of four factors (*Oct3/4*, *Sox2*, c-Myc, and *Klf4*) to differentiated cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Utilizing the four genes previously listed, the differentiated cells are "reprogrammed" into pluripotent stem cells, allowing for the generation of pluripotent/embryonic stem cells without the embryo.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The morphology and growth factors of these lab induced pluripotent cells, are equivalent to embryonic stem cells, leading these cells to be known as induced pluripotent stem cells (iPS cells).
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] This observation was observed in mouse pluripotent stem cells, originally, but now can be performed in human adult fibroblasts using the same four genes.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Because ethical concerns regarding embryonic stem cells typically are about their derivation from terminated embryos, it is believed that reprogramming to these iPS cells may be less controversial.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] This may enable the generation of patient specific ES cell lines that could potentially be used for cell replacement therapies.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] In addition, this will allow the generation of ES cell lines from patients with a variety of genetic diseases and will provide invaluable models to study those diseases.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] On January 16, 2008, a California-based company, Stemagen, announced that they had created the first mature cloned human embryos from single skin cells taken from adults.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] These embryos can be harvested for patient matching embryonic stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The online edition of *Nature Medicine* published a study on January 24, 2005, which stated that the human embryonic stem cells available for federally funded research are contaminated with non-human molecules from the culture medium used to grow the cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] It is a common technique to use mouse cells and other animal cells to maintain the pluripotency of actively dividing stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] The problem was discovered when non-human sialic acid in the growth medium was found to compromise the potential uses of the embryonic stem cells in humans, according to scientists at the University of California, San Diego.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] However, a study published in the online edition of *Lancet Medical Journal* on March 8, 2005, detailed information about a new stem cell line that was derived from human embryos under completely cell- and serum-free conditions.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] After more than 6 months of undifferentiated proliferation, these cells demonstrated the potential to form derivatives of all three embryonic germ layers both *in vitro* and in teratomas.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] These properties were also successfully maintained (for more than 30 passages) with the established stem cell lines.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Muse cells (Multi-lineage differentiating stress enduring cell) are non-cancerous pluripotent stem cell found in adults.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] They were discovered in 2010 by Mari Dezawa and her research group.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Muse cells reside in the connective tissue of nearly every organ including the umbilical cord, bone marrow and peripheral blood.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] They are collectable from commercially obtainable mesenchymal cells such as human fibroblasts, bone marrow-mesenchymal stem cells and adipose-derived stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Muse cells are able to generate cells representative of all three germ layers from a single cell both spontaneously and under cytokine induction.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Expression of pluripotency genes and triploblastic differentiation are self-renewable over generations.
[src:stem-cell-biology/embryonic-stem-cell] Muse cells do not undergo teratoma formation when transplanted into a host environment in vivo, eradicating the risk of tumorigenesis through unbridled cell proliferation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Pluripotent stem cells hold promise in the field of regenerative medicine.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Because they can propagate indefinitely, as well as give rise to every other cell type in the body (such as neurons, heart, pancreatic, and liver cells), they represent a single source of cells that could be used to replace those lost to damage or disease.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The best-known type of pluripotent stem cell is the embryonic stem cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] However, since the generation of embryonic stem cells involves the destruction (or at least manipulation) of a pre-implantation stage embryo, there has been much controversy surrounding their use.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Patient-matched embryonic stem cell lines can now be derived using somatic cell nuclear transfer (SCNT).
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Since iPSCs can be derived directly from adult tissues, they not only bypass the need for embryos, but can be made in a patient-matched manner, which means that each individual could have their own pluripotent stem cell line.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] These unlimited supplies of autologous cells could be used to generate transplants without the risk of immune rejection.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] While the iPSC technology has not yet advanced to a stage where therapeutic transplants have been deemed safe, iPSCs are readily being used in personalized drug discovery efforts and understanding the patient-specific basis of disease.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Yamanaka named iPSCs with a lower case "i" due to the popularity of the iPod and other Apple products.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In his Nobel seminar, Yamanaka cited the earlier seminal work of Harold Weintraub on the role of myoblast determination protein 1 (MyoD) in reprogramming cell fate to a muscle lineage as an important precursor to the discovery of iPSCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] iPSCs are typically derived by introducing products of specific sets of pluripotency-associated genes, or "reprogramming factors", into a given cell type.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The original set of reprogramming factors (also dubbed Yamanaka factors) are the transcription factors Oct4 (Pou5f1), Sox2, Klf4 and cMyc.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] While this combination is most conventional in producing iPSCs, each of the factors can be functionally replaced by related transcription factors, miRNAs, small molecules, or even non-related genes such as lineage specifiers.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] It is also clear that pro-mitotic factors such as C-MYC/L-MYC or repression of cell cycle checkpoints, such as p53, are conduits to creating a compliant cellular state for iPSC reprogramming.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] iPSC derivation is typically a slow and inefficient process, taking one–two weeks for mouse cells and three–four weeks for human cells, with efficiencies around 0.01–0.1%.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] However, considerable advances have been made in improving the efficiency and the time it takes to obtain iPSCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Upon introduction of reprogramming factors, cells begin to form colonies that resemble pluripotent stem cells, which can be isolated based on their morphology, conditions that select for their growth, or through expression of surface markers or reporter genes.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Induced pluripotent stem cells were first generated by Shinya Yamanaka and Kazutoshi Takahashi at Kyoto University, Japan, in 2006.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] They hypothesized that genes important to embryonic stem cell (ESC) function might be able to induce an embryonic state in adult cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] They chose twenty-four genes previously identified as important in ESCs and used retroviruses to deliver these genes to mouse fibroblasts.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The fibroblasts were engineered so that any cells reactivating the ESC-specific gene, Fbx15, could be isolated using antibiotic selection.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Upon delivery of all twenty-four factors, ESC-like colonies emerged that reactivated the Fbx15 reporter and could propagate indefinitely.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] To identify the genes necessary for reprogramming, the researchers removed one factor at a time from the pool of twenty-four.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] By this process, they identified four factors, Oct4, Sox2, cMyc, and Klf4, which were each necessary and together sufficient to generate ESC-like colonies under selection for reactivation of Fbx15.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In June 2007, three separate research groups, including that of Yamanaka's, a Harvard/University of California, Los Angeles collaboration, and a group at MIT, published studies that substantially improved on the reprogramming approach, giving rise to iPSCs that were indistinguishable from ESCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Unlike the first generation of iPSCs, these second generation iPSCs produced viable chimeric mice and contributed to the mouse germline, thereby achieving the 'gold standard' for pluripotent stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] These second-generation iPSCs were derived from mouse fibroblasts by retroviral-mediated expression of the same four transcription factors (Oct4, Sox2, cMyc, Klf4).
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] However, instead of using Fbx15 to select for pluripotent cells, the researchers used Nanog, a gene that is functionally important in ESCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] By using this different strategy, the researchers created iPSCs that were functionally identical to ESCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Reprogramming of human cells to iPSCs was reported in November 2007 by two independent research groups: Shinya Yamanaka of Kyoto University, Japan, who pioneered the original iPSC method, and James Thomson of University of Wisconsin-Madison who was the first to derive human embryonic stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Obtaining fibroblasts to produce iPSCs involves a skin biopsy, and there has been a push towards identifying cell types that are more easily accessible.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2008, iPSCs were derived from human keratinocytes, which could be obtained from a single hair pluck.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2010, iPSCs were derived from peripheral blood cells, and in 2012, iPSCs were made from renal epithelial cells in the urine.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Other considerations for starting cell type include mutational load (for example, skin cells may harbor more mutations due to UV exposure), time it takes to expand the population of starting cells, and the ability to differentiate into a given cell type.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The generation of induced pluripotent cells is crucially dependent on the transcription factors used for the induction.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Oct-3/4 and certain products of the Sox gene family (Sox1, Sox2, Sox3, and Sox15) have been identified as crucial transcriptional regulators involved in the induction process whose absence makes induction impossible.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Additional genes, however, including certain members of the Klf family (Klf1, Klf2, Klf4, and Klf5), the Myc family (c-myc, L-myc, and N-myc), Nanog, and LIN28, have been identified to increase the induction efficiency.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Genomic Insertion: genomic integration of the transcription factors limits the utility of the transcription factor approach because of the risk of mutations being inserted into the target cell's genome.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] A common strategy for avoiding genomic insertion has been to use a different vector for input.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Plasmids, adenoviruses, and transposon vectors have all been explored, but these often come with the tradeoff of lower throughput.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Tumorigenicity: Depending on the methods used, reprogramming of adult cells to obtain iPSCs may pose significant risks that could limit their use in humans.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] For example, if viruses are used to genomically alter the cells, the expression of oncogenes (cancer-causing genes) may potentially be triggered.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In February 2008, scientists announced the discovery of a technique that could remove oncogenes after the induction of pluripotency, thereby increasing the potential use of iPS cells in human diseases.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In another study, Yamanaka reported that one can create iPSCs without the oncogene c-Myc.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The process took longer and was not as efficient, but the resulting chimeras did not develop cancer.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Inactivation or deletion of the tumor suppressor p53, which is a key regulator of cancer, significantly increases reprogramming efficiency.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Thus there seems to be a tradeoff between reprogramming efficiency and tumor generation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Incomplete reprogramming: reprogramming also faces the challenge of completeness.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] This is particularly challenging because the genome-wide epigenetic code must be reformatted to that of the target cell type in order to fully reprogram a cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The table on the right summarizes the key strategies and techniques used to develop iPS cells in the first five years after Yamanaka et al.'s 2006 breakthrough.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Rows of similar colors represent studies that used similar strategies for reprogramming.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] One of the main strategies for avoiding problems (1) and (2) has been to use small molecules that can mimic the effects of transcription factors.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] These compounds can compensate for a reprogramming factor that does not effectively target the genome or fails at reprogramming for another reason; thus they raise reprogramming efficiency.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] They also avoid the problem of genomic integration, which in some cases contributes to tumor genesis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Key studies using such strategy were conducted in 2008.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Melton et al. studied the effects of histone deacetylase (HDAC) inhibitor valproic acid.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] They found that it increased reprogramming efficiency 100-fold (compared to Yamanaka's traditional transcription factor method).
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The researchers proposed that this compound was mimicking the signaling that is usually caused by the transcription factor c-Myc.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] A similar type of compensation mechanism was proposed to mimic the effects of Sox2.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2008, Ding et al. used the inhibition of histone methyl transferase (HMT) with BIX-01294 in combination with the activation of calcium channels in the plasma membrane in order to increase reprogramming efficiency.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Deng et al. of Beijing University reported in July 2013 that induced pluripotent stem cells can be created without any genetic modification.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] They used a cocktail of seven small-molecule compounds including DZNep to induce the mouse somatic cells into stem cells which they called CiPS cells with the efficiency – at 0.2% – comparable to those using standard iPSC production techniques.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The CiPS cells were introduced into developing mouse embryos and were found to contribute to all major cell types, proving its pluripotency.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Ding *et al*. demonstrated an alternative to transcription factor reprogramming through the use of drug-like chemicals.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Adding a third compound known to be involved in the cell survival pathway, thiazovivin further increases the efficiency by 200 fold.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Using the combination of these three compounds also decreased the reprogramming process of the human fibroblasts from four weeks to two weeks.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In April 2009, it was demonstrated that generation of iPS cells is possible without any genetic alteration of the adult cell: a repeated treatment of the cells with certain proteins channeled into the cells via poly-arginine anchors was sufficient to induce pluripotency.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The acronym given for those iPSCs is **piPSCs** (protein-induced pluripotent stem cells).
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Another key strategy for avoiding problems such as tumorgenesis and low throughput has been to use alternate forms of vectors: adenoviruses, plasmids, and naked DNA or protein compounds.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2008, Hochedlinger et al. used an adenovirus to transport the requisite four transcription factors into the DNA of skin and liver cells of mice, resulting in cells identical to ESCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The adenovirus is unique from other vectors like viruses and retroviruses because it does not incorporate any of its own genes into the targeted host and avoids the potential for insertional mutagenesis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2009, Freed et al. demonstrated successful reprogramming of human fibroblasts to iPS cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Another advantage of using adenoviruses is that they only need to present for a brief amount of time in order for effective reprogramming to take place.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Also in 2008, Yamanaka et al. found that they could transfer the four necessary genes with a plasmid.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The Yamanaka group successfully reprogrammed mouse cells by transfection with two plasmid constructs carrying the reprogramming factors; the first plasmid expressed c-Myc, while the second expressed the other three factors (Oct4, Klf4, and Sox2).
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Although the plasmid methods avoid viruses, they still require cancer-promoting genes to accomplish reprogramming.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The other main issue with these methods is that they tend to be much less efficient compared to retroviral methods.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Furthermore, transfected plasmids have been shown to integrate into the host genome and therefore they still pose the risk of insertional mutagenesis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Because non-retroviral approaches have demonstrated such low efficiency levels, researchers have attempted to effectively rescue the technique with what is known as the PiggyBac Transposon System.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Several studies have demonstrated that this system can effectively deliver the key reprogramming factors without leaving footprint mutations in the host cell genome.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The PiggyBac Transposon System involves the re-excision of exogenous genes, which eliminates the issue of insertional mutagenesis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In light of difficulties that other labs had replicating the results of the surprising study, in March 2014, one of the co-authors has called for the articles to be retracted.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] On 4 June 2014, the lead author, Obokata agreed to retract both the papers after she was found to have committed 'research misconduct' as concluded in an investigation by RIKEN on 1 April 2014.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] MicroRNAs are short RNA molecules that bind to complementary sequences on messenger RNA and block expression of a gene.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Measuring variations in microRNA expression in iPS cells can be used to predict their differentiation potential.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Addition of microRNAs can also be used to enhance iPS potential.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] ES cell-specific microRNA molecules (such as miR-291, miR-294 and miR-295) enhance the efficiency of induced pluripotency by acting downstream of c-Myc.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] MicroRNAs can also block expression of repressors of Yamanaka's four transcription factors, and there may be additional mechanisms that induce reprogramming even in the absence of added exogenous transcription factors.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Gene expression and genome-wide H3K4me3 and H3K27me3 were found to be extremely similar between ES and iPS cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The task of producing iPS cells continues to be challenging due to the six problems mentioned above.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] A key tradeoff to overcome is that between efficiency and genomic integration.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Most methods that do not rely on the integration of transgenes are inefficient, while those that do rely on the integration of transgenes face the problems of incomplete reprogramming and tumor genesis, although a vast number of techniques and methods have been attempted.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Another large set of strategies is to perform a proteomic characterization of iPS cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Further studies and new strategies should generate optimal solutions to the five main challenges.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] One approach might attempt to combine the positive attributes of these strategies into an ultimately effective technique for reprogramming cells to iPS cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Another approach is the use of iPS cells derived from patients to identify therapeutic drugs able to rescue a phenotype.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] For instance, iPS cell lines derived from patients affected by ectodermal dysplasia syndrome (EEC), in which the p63 gene is mutated, display abnormal epithelial commitment that could be partially rescued by a small compound.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] An attractive feature of human iPS cells is the ability to derive them from adult patients to study the cellular basis of human disease.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Since iPS cells are self-renewing and pluripotent, they represent a theoretically unlimited source of patient-derived cells which can be turned into any type of cell in the body.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In many instances, the patient-derived iPS cells exhibit cellular defects not observed in iPS cells from healthy subjects, providing insight into the pathophysiology of the disease.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] An international collaborated project, StemBANCC, was formed in 2012 to build a collection of iPS cell lines for drug screening for a variety of diseases.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Managed by the University of Oxford, the effort pooled funds and resources from 10 pharmaceutical companies and 23 universities.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The goal is to generate a library of 1,500 iPS cell lines which will be used in early drug testing by providing a simulated human disease environment.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Furthermore, combining hiPSC technology and small molecule or genetically encoded voltage and calcium indicators provided a large-scale and high-throughput platform for cardiovascular drug safety screening.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] A proof-of-concept of using induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs) to generate human organ for transplantation was reported by researchers from Japan.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Human 'liver buds' (iPSC-LBs) were grown from a mixture of three different kinds of stem cells: hepatocyte (for liver function) coaxed from iPSCs; endothelial stem cells (to form lining of blood vessels) from umbilical cord blood; and mesenchymal stem cells (to form connective tissue).
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] This new approach allows different cell types to self-organize into a complex organ, mimicking the process in fetal development.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] After growing *in vitro* for a few days, the liver buds were transplanted into mice where the 'liver' quickly connected with the host blood vessels and continued to grow.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Most importantly, it performed regular liver functions including metabolizing drugs and producing liver-specific proteins.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Further studies will monitor the longevity of the transplanted organ in the host body (ability to integrate or avoid rejection) and whether it will transform into tumors.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2021, a switchable Yamanaka factors-reprogramming-based approach for regeneration of damaged heart without tumor-formation was demonstrated in mice and was successful if the intervention was carried out immediately before or after a heart attack.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2020, Japan first transplanted lab-grown heart cells into a human patient.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Embryonic cord-blood cells were induced into pluripotent stem cells using plasmid DNA.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Using cell surface endothelial/pericytic markers CD31 and CD146, researchers identified 'vascular progenitor', the high-quality, multipotent vascular stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] After the iPS cells were injected directly into the vitreous of the damaged retina of mice, the stem cells engrafted into the retina, grew and repaired the vascular vessels.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Labelled iPSCs-derived NSCs injected into laboratory animals with brain lesions were shown to migrate to the lesions and some motor function improvement was observed.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Beating cardiac muscle cells, iPSC-derived cardiomyocytes, can be mass-produced using chemically defined differentiation protocols.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] These protocols typically modulate the same developmental signaling pathways required for heart development.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] These iPSC-cardiomyocytes can recapitulate genetic arrhythmias and cardiac drug responses, since they exhibit the same genetic background as the patient from which they were derived.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In June 2014, Takara Bio received technology transfer from iHeart Japan, a venture company from Kyoto University's iPS Cell Research Institute, to make it possible to exclusively use technologies and patents that induce differentiation of iPS cells into cardiomyocytes in Asia.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The company announced the idea of selling cardiomyocytes to pharmaceutical companies and universities to help develop new drugs for heart disease.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] On March 9, 2018, the Specified Regenerative Medicine Committee of Osaka University officially approved the world's first clinical research plan to transplant a "myocardial sheet" made from iPS cells into the heart of patients with severe heart failure.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Osaka University announced that it had filed an application with the Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare on the same day.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] On May 16, 2018, the clinical research plan was approved by the Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare's expert group with a condition.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In October 2019, a group at Okayama University developed a model of ischemic heart disease using cardiomyocytes differentiated from iPS cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Although a pint of donated blood contains about two trillion red blood cells and over 107 million blood donations are collected globally, there is still a critical need for blood for transfusion.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2014, type O red blood cells were synthesized at the Scottish National Blood Transfusion Service from iPSC.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The cells were induced to become a mesoderm and then blood cells and then red blood cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The final step was to make them eject their nuclei and mature properly.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Type O can be transfused into all patients.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Human clinical trials were not expected to begin before 2016.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The first human clinical trial using autologous iPSCs was approved by the Japan Ministry Health and was to be conducted in 2014 at the Riken Center for Developmental Biology in Kobe.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] However the trial was suspended after Japan's new regenerative medicine laws came into effect in November 2015.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] More specifically, an existing set of guidelines was strengthened to have the force of law (previously mere recommendations). iPSCs derived from skin cells from six patients with wet age-related macular degeneration were reprogrammed to differentiate into retinal pigment epithelial (RPE) cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The cell sheet would be transplanted into the affected retina where the degenerated RPE tissue was excised.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Safety and vision restoration monitoring were to last one to three years.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In March 2017, a team led by Masayo Takahashi completed the first successful transplant of iPS-derived retinal cells from a donor into the eye of a person with advanced macular degeneration.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] However it was reported that they are now having complications.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The benefits of using autologous iPSCs are that there is theoretically no risk of rejection and that it eliminates the need to use embryonic stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] However, these iPSCs were derived from another person.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] New clinical trials involving iPSCs are now ongoing not only in Japan, but also in the US and Europe.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Research in 2021 on the trial registry Clinicaltrials.gov identified 129 trial listings mentioning iPSCs, but most were non-interventional.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2026, Japan’s Pharmaceutical Affairs Council recommended that the Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare extend conditional approval to two allogeneic iPSC-based therapeutic products, Amchepry for Parkinson’s and ReHeart for severe heart failure.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] To make iPSC-based regenerative medicine technologies available to more patients, it is necessary to create universal iPSCs that can be transplanted independently of haplotypes of HLA.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The current strategy for the creation of universal iPSCs has two main goals: to remove HLA expression and to prevent NK cells attacks due to deletion of HLA.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Deletion of the B2M and CIITA genes using the CRISPR/Cas9 system has been reported to suppress the expression of HLA class I and class II, respectively.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] To avoid NK cell attacks. transduction of ligands inhibiting NK-cells, such as HLA-E and CD47 has been used.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] HLA-C is left unchanged, since the 12 common HLA-C alleles are enough to cover 95% of the world's population.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] A multipotent mesenchymal stem cell, when induced into pluripotence, holds great promise to slow or reverse aging phenotypes.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] Such anti-aging properties were demonstrated in early clinical trials in 2017.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] In 2020, Stanford University researchers concluded after studying elderly mice that old human cells when subjected to the Yamanaka factors, might rejuvenate and become nearly indistinguishable from their younger counterparts.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] A review published in 2025 examines the development of hypoimmunogenic pluripotent stem cells (hPSCs) using advanced genome editing techniques aimed at reducing the risk of immune rejection in allogeneic cell therapy.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] These hPSCs are engineered to lack expression of major histocompatibility complex (MHC) class I and II molecules, while expressing immune-modulatory genes such as PD-L1, CD47, and HLA-G.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] This combination enhances immune evasion and supports the concept of universal donor cells that do not require human leukocyte antigen (HLA) matching.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] The integration of suicide gene systems, such as inducible Caspase-9, further enhances safety by enabling the selective elimination of cells in the event of malignancy.
[src:stem-cell-biology/induced-pluripotent-stem-cell] These strategies are intended to improve the safety, scalability, and accessibility of regenerative treatments.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Regenerative medicine also includes the possibility of growing tissues and organs in the laboratory and implanting them when the body cannot heal itself.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] When the cell source for a regenerated organ is derived from the patient's own tissue or cells, the challenge of organ transplant rejection via immunological mismatch is circumvented.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] This approach could alleviate the problem of the shortage of organs available for donation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Some of the biomedical approaches within the field of regenerative medicine may involve the use of stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] The ancient Greeks postulated whether parts of the body could be regenerated in the 700s BC.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Skin grafting, invented in the late 19th century, can be thought of as the earliest major attempt to recreate bodily tissue to restore structure and function.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Advances in transplanting body parts in the 20th century further pushed the theory that body parts could regenerate and grow new cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] These advances led to tissue engineering, and from this field, the study of regenerative medicine expanded and began to take hold.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] This began with cellular therapy, which led to the stem cell research that is widely being conducted today.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] The first cell therapies were intended to slow the aging process.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] This began in the 1930s with Paul Niehans, a Swiss doctor who was known to have treated famous historical figures such as Pope Pius XII, Charlie Chaplin, and king Ibn Saud of Saudi Arabia.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Niehans would inject cells of young animals (usually lambs or calves) into his patients in an attempt to rejuvenate them.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] In 1956, a more sophisticated process was created to treat leukemia by inserting bone marrow from a healthy person into a patient with leukemia.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] This process worked mostly due to both the donor and receiver in this case being identical twins.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Nowadays, bone marrow can be taken from people who are similar enough to the patient who needs the cells to prevent rejection.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] The term "regenerative medicine" was first used in a 1992 article on hospital administration by Leland Kaiser.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Kaiser's paper closes with a series of short paragraphs on future technologies that will impact hospitals.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] The term was brought into the popular culture in 1999 by William A.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Haseltine when he coined the term during a conference on Lake Como, to describe interventions that restore to normal function that which is damaged by disease, injured by trauma, or worn by time.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Haseltine was briefed on the project to isolate human embryonic stem cells and embryonic germ cells at Geron Corporation in collaboration with researchers at the University of Wisconsin–Madison and Johns Hopkins School of Medicine.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] He recognized that these cells' unique ability to differentiate into all the cell types of the human body (pluripotency) had the potential to develop into a new kind of regenerative therapy.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Later, Haseltine would go on to explain that regenerative medicine acknowledges the reality that most people, regardless of which illness they have or which treatment they require, simply want to be restored to normal health.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Designed to be applied broadly, the original definition includes cell and stem cell therapies, gene therapy, tissue engineering, genomic medicine, personalized medicine, biomechanical prosthetics, recombinant proteins, and antibody treatments.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] It also includes more familiar chemical pharmacopeia—in short, any intervention that restores a person to normal health.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] In addition to functioning as shorthand for a wide range of technologies and treatments, the term "regenerative medicine" is also patient friendly.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] It solves the problem that confusing or intimidating language discourages patients.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] The term regenerative medicine is increasingly conflated with research on stem cell therapies.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Some academic programs and departments retain the original broader definition while others use it to describe work on stem cell research.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] In March 2000, Haseltine, Antony Atala, M.D., Michael D.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] West, Ph.D., and other leading researchers founded *E-Biomed: The Journal of Regenerative Medicine*.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] The peer-reviewed journal facilitated discourse around regenerative medicine by publishing innovative research on stem cell therapies, gene therapies, tissue engineering, and biomechanical prosthetics.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] The Society for Regenerative Medicine, later renamed the Regenerative Medicine and Stem Cell Biology Society, served a similar purpose, creating a community of like-minded experts from around the world.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] In June 2008, at the Hospital Clínic de Barcelona, Professor Paolo Macchiarini and his team, of the University of Barcelona, performed the first tissue engineered trachea (wind pipe) transplantation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Adult stem cells were extracted from the patient's bone marrow, grown into a large population, and matured into cartilage cells, or chondrocytes, using an adaptive method originally devised for treating osteoarthritis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] The team then seeded the newly grown chondrocytes, as well as epithelial cells, into a decellularised (free of donor cells) tracheal segment that was donated from a 51-year-old transplant donor who had died of cerebral hemorrhage.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] After four days of seeding, the graft was used to replace the patient's left main bronchus.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] After one month, a biopsy elicited local bleeding, indicating that the blood vessels had already grown back successfully.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] In 2009, the SENS Foundation was launched, with its stated aim as "the application of regenerative medicine – defined to include the repair of living cells and extracellular material in situ – to the diseases and disabilities of ageing".
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] In 2012, Professor Paolo Macchiarini and his team improved upon the 2008 implant by transplanting a laboratory-made trachea seeded with the patient's own cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] In 2016, Paolo Macchiarini was fired from Karolinska University in Sweden due to falsified test results and lies.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] The TV-show Experimenten aired on Swedish Television and detailed all the lies and falsified results.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] In China, institutes dedicated to regenerative medicine are run by the Chinese Academy of Sciences, Tsinghua University, and the Chinese University of Hong Kong, among others.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Current research in regenerative medicine spans a continuous spectrum from fundamental cell biology to clinical translational engineering, focusing on deciphering and manipulating the signaling pathways that govern tissue morphogenesis, cellular differentiation, and scarless wound healing.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Rather than merely managing chronic symptoms, active laboratory investigations aim to understand why adult mammalian tissues lose the regenerative capacities inherent in lower vertebrates and human embryonic states.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] A major bottleneck in ongoing research is solving the scalability of functional vascularization, as complex engineered tissues cannot survive past the limits of oxygen diffusion without an integrated capillary network.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Cardiovascular regenerative medicine focuses on repairing damaged myocardial tissue, heart valves, and peripheral blood vessels, primarily targeting ischemic heart disease and congenital heart defects.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Because adult mammalian cardiomyocytes possess highly restricted proliferative capacity, therapeutic strategies utilize engineered cardiac patches, cell-seeded hydrogels, and decellularized extracellular matrix (ECM) components to stimulate localized myocardial repair after a myocardial infarction.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Clinical and pre-clinical research focuses heavily on using induced pluripotent stem cell-derived cardiomyocytes (hiPSC-CMs) and vascular endothelial cells embedded within porous, biomimetic polymeric scaffolds to ensure functional electrical coupling and host tissue integration.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Lung tissue engineering focuses on developing functional respiratory structures to treat end-stage pulmonary diseases, such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), pulmonary fibrosis, and acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS).
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Due to the complex, highly vascularized three-dimensional architecture of the lung, which comprises over forty distinct cell types and a delicate alveolar-capillary basement membrane, whole-organ biofabrication typically relies on decellularized donor lung scaffolds.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] This process strips away immunogenic cellular material while preserving the native extracellular matrix geometry and mechanical compliance required for ventilation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Research strategies prioritize the multi-lineage recellularization of these scaffolds using patient-specific induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs) differentiated into alveolar epithelial cells (type I and II) and microvascular endothelial cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Additionally, biomimetic microfluidic platforms, or "lung-on-a-chip" models, are utilized to study cellular shear stress and gas-exchange dynamics, serving as precursors to transplantable bioartificial lung devices.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Musculoskeletal applications represent a commercially mature sector of tissue engineering, focusing on the repair of critical-sized bone defects, articular cartilage lesions, and volumetric muscle loss.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] For orthopedic bone regeneration, therapeutic approaches utilize osteoconductive and osteoinductive scaffolds composed of bioceramics (such as hydroxyapatite and beta-tricalcium phosphate), biodegradable polymers, or composite hydrogels.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] These matrices serve as physical frameworks that recruit endogenous mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs) and promote osteogenesis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] A critical challenge in bone tissue engineering is achieving adequate neovascularization within the core of large scaffolds to prevent core necrosis before host capillary ingrowth occurs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Consequently, modern biomaterial designs often implement multi-scale porosity, integrating smaller voids for nutrient diffusion with macro-channels greater than 100 micrometers, to facilitate deep cellular infiltration, matrix mineralization, and functional host tissue integration.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Regenerative strategies within the central nervous system (CNS) and peripheral nervous system (PNS) address severe impairments caused by spinal cord injuries, ischemic strokes, and neurodegenerative disorders such as Parkinson's disease.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] The therapeutic microenvironment of the adult brain and spinal cord is highly inhibitory to axon growth due to the formation of glial scars and chondroitin sulfate proteoglycans.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Neuroregeneration research utilizes injectable hydrogels, shear-thinning biomaterials, and electrospun guidance conduits to physically bridge lesion cavities.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Dermal regeneration involves the development of bioengineered skin substitutes and advanced wound dressings to treat deep third-degree burns, diabetic foot ulcers, and extensive chronic wounds.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Unlike traditional occlusive dressings, regenerative skin scaffolds provide a temporary, porous extracellular matrix analog that coordinates cellular ingress, granulation tissue formation, and re-epithelialization.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Commercially available matrices utilize decellularized human or bovine dermal matrices, synthetic biodegradable polymers (such as polycaprolactone), and naturally derived marine biomaterials, including acellular fish skin graphics rich in omega-3 fatty acids.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] These matrices are designed to modulate the localized inflammatory response, suppress bacterial colonization, and recruit host fibroblasts and keratinocytes to restore functional, vascularized skin tissue while minimizing scar formation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Regenerative medicine has been studied by dentists to find ways that damaged teeth can be repaired and restored to obtain natural structure and function.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Dental tissues are often damaged due to tooth decay, and are often deemed to be irreplaceable except by synthetic or metal dental fillings or crowns, which requires further damage to be done to the teeth by drilling into them to prevent the loss of an entire tooth.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Researchers from King's College London have created a drug called Tideglusib that claims to have the ability to regrow dentin, the second layer of the tooth beneath the enamel which encases and protects the pulp (often referred to as the nerve).
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Animal studies conducted on mice in Japan in 2007 show great possibilities in regenerating an entire tooth.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Some mice had a tooth extracted and the cells from bioengineered tooth germs were implanted into them and allowed to grow.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] The result were perfectly functioning and healthy teeth, complete with all three layers, as well as roots.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] These teeth also had the necessary ligaments to stay rooted in its socket and allow for natural shifting.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] They contrast with traditional dental implants, which are restricted to one spot as they are drilled into the jawbone.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] A person's baby teeth are known to contain stem cells that can be used for regeneration of the dental pulp after a root canal treatment or injury.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] These cells can also be used to repair damage from periodontitis, an advanced form of gum disease that causes bone loss and severe gum recession.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Research is still being done to see if these stem cells are viable enough to grow into completely new teeth.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Some parents even opt to keep their children's baby teeth in special storage with the thought that, when older, the children could use the stem cells within them to treat a condition.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Extracellular matrix materials are commercially available and are used in reconstructive surgery, treatment of chronic wounds, and some orthopedic surgeries; as of January 2017 clinical studies were under way to use them in heart surgery to try to repair damaged heart tissue.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] The use of fish skin with its natural constituent of omega 3, has been developed by an Icelandic company Kereceis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Omega 3 is a natural anti-inflammatory, and the fish skin material acts as a scaffold for cell regeneration.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] In 2016 their product *Omega3 Wound* was approved by the FDA for the treatment of chronic wounds and burns.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] In 2021 the FDA gave approval for *Omega3 Surgibind* to be used in surgical applications including plastic surgery.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Though uses of cord blood beyond blood and immunological disorders is speculative, some research has been done in other areas.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Any such potential beyond blood and immunological uses is limited by the fact that cord cells are hematopoietic stem cells (which can differentiate only into blood cells), and not pluripotent stem cells (such as embryonic stem cells, which can differentiate into any type of tissue).
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Cord blood has been studied as a treatment for diabetes.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] However, apart from blood disorders, the use of cord blood for other diseases is not a routine clinical modality and remains a major challenge for the stem cell community.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] The potential use of developmental bioelectricity in regenerative medicine is under active investigation, with particular interest in future organ and limb regeneration guided by bioelectric stimulation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Developmental bioelectricity refers to endogenous ion flows and voltage gradients across cell membranes (Vmem) in excitable (able to create an action potential) and non-excitable tissues that provide instructive cues for growth.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] These bioelectric states, set by ion channels and pumps, are propagated through gap-junction coupling and together with chemical gradients and physical forces they form long-range patterning circuits.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Through voltage-sensitive signalling pathways, changes in Vmem modulate gene expression and cell behaviours (proliferation, migration, differentiation), thereby shaping tissue growth and polarity.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Experiments in vertebrate and invertebrate models indicate that bioelectric cues can steer regeneration.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] In Xenopus tadpoles, activating a proton pump (V-ATPase) that moves hydrogen ions out of cells is necessary for tail regrowth and can restore regeneration during a normally refractory stage; in adult Zebrafish, inhibiting the same pump impairs fin regrowth.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] In Planarians, brief electrical perturbations can cause tail pieces to form heads (including two-headed animals) or to regenerate heads resembling other species.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] In adult frogs, a 24-hour treatment with a drug-delivering ‘BioDome’ device initiated long-term hindlimb regrowth with multi-tissue repair and functional recovery.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Proposed techniques combine pharmacological control of ion channels and gap junctions, optogenetic actuators to write Vmem patterns with light, and devices that condition the injury microenvironment or apply controlled direct-current fields.
[src:stem-cell-biology/regenerative-medicine] Proposed tools include voltage-sensitive dyes, microelectrodes, and wearable or implantable stimulators.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Scientists are studying the various components of the niche and trying to replicate the *in vivo* niche conditions *in vitro*.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] This is because for regenerative therapies, cell proliferation and differentiation must be controlled in flasks or plates, so that sufficient quantity of the proper cell type are produced prior to being introduced back into the patient for therapy.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Human embryonic stem cells are often grown in fibrotastic growth factor-2 containing, fetal bovine serum supplemented media.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] They are grown on a feeder layer of cells, which is believed to be supportive in maintaining the pluripotent characteristics of embryonic stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] However, even these conditions may not truly mimic *in vivo* niche conditions.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Adult stem cells remain in an undifferentiated state throughout adult life.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] However, when they are cultured *in vitro*, they often undergo an 'aging' process in which their morphology is changed and their proliferative capacity is decreased.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] It is believed that correct culturing conditions of adult stem cells needs to be improved so that adult stem cells can maintain their stemness over time.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Though the concept of stem cell niche was prevailing in vertebrates, the first characterization of stem cell niche in vivo was worked out in *Drosophila* germinal development.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] By continuous intravital imaging in mice, researchers were able to explore the structure of the stem cell niche and to obtain the fate of individual stem cells (SCs) and their progeny over time in vivo.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] In particular in intestinal crypt, two distinct groups of SCs have been identified: the "border stem cells" located in the upper part of the niche at the interface with transit amplifying cells (TAs), and "central stem cells" located at the crypt base.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The proliferative potential of the two groups was unequal and correlated with the cells' location (central or border).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] It was also shown that the two SC compartments acted in accord to maintain a constant cell population and a steady cellular turnover.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] A similar dependence of self-renewal potential on proximity to the niche border was reported in the context of hair follicle, in an in vivo live-imaging study.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] This bi-compartmental structure of stem cell niche has been mathematically modeled to obtain the optimal architecture that leads to the maximum delay in double-hit mutant production.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] They found that the bi-compartmental SC architecture minimizes the rate of two-hit mutant production compared to the single SC compartment model.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Moreover, the minimum probability of double-hit mutant generation corresponds to purely symmetric division of SCs with a large proliferation rate of border stem cells along with a small, but non-zero, proliferation rate of central stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Stem cell niches harboring continuously dividing cells, such as those located at the base of the intestinal gland, are maintained at small population size.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] This presents a challenge to the maintenance of multicellular tissues, as small populations of asexually dividing individuals will accumulate deleterious mutations through genetic drift and succumb to mutational meltdown.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Therefore, the population size of the stem cell niche represents an evolutionary trade-off between the probability of cancer formation and the rate of aging.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Germline stem cells (GSCs) are found in organisms that continuously produce sperm and eggs until they are sterile.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] These specialized stem cells reside in the GSC niche, the initial site for gamete production, which is composed of the GSCs, somatic stem cells, and other somatic cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] In particular, the GSC niche is well studied in the genetic model organism *Drosophila melanogaster* and has provided an extensive understanding of the molecular basis of stem cell regulation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] In *Drosophila melanogaster*, the GSC niche resides in the anterior-most region of each ovariole, known as the germarium.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The GSC niche consists of necessary somatic cells-terminal filament cells, cap cells, escort cells, and other stem cells which function to maintain the GSCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The GSC niche holds on average 2–3 GSCs, which are directly attached to somatic cap cells and Escort stem cells, which send maintenance signals directly to the GSCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] GSCs are easily identified through histological staining against vasa protein (to identify germ cells) and 1B1 protein (to outline cell structures and a germline specific fusome structure).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Their physical attachment to the cap cells is necessary for their maintenance and activity.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Because of the abundant genetic tools available for use in *Drosophila melanogaster* and the ease of detecting GSCs through histological stainings, researchers have uncovered several molecular pathways controlling GSC maintenance and activity.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The Bone Morphogenetic Protein (BMP) ligands Decapentaplegic (Dpp) and Glass-bottom-boat (Gbb) ligand are directly signalled to the GSCs, and are essential for GSC maintenance and self-renewal.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] BMP signalling in the niche functions to directly repress expression of *Bag-of-marbles* (*Bam*) in GSCs, which is up-regulated in developing cystoblast cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Loss of function of *dpp* in the niche results in de-repression of Bam in GSCs, resulting in rapid differentiation of the GSCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Along with BMP signalling, cap cells also signal other molecules to GSCs: Yb and Piwi.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Both of these molecules are required non-autonomously to the GSCs for proliferation-*piwi* is also required autonomously in the GSCs for proliferation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] In the germarium, BMP signaling has a short-range effect, therefore the physical attachment of GSCs to cap cells is important for maintenance and activity.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The GSCs are physically attached to the cap cells by *Drosophila* E-cadherin (DE-cadherin) adherens junctions and if this physical attachment is lost GSCs will differentiate and lose their identity as a stem cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The gene encoding DE-cadherin, *shotgun* (*shg*), and a gene encoding Beta-catenin ortholog, *armadillo*, control this physical attachment.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] A GTPase molecule, rab11, is involved in cell trafficking of DE-cadherins.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Knocking out *rab11* in GSCs results in detachment of GSCs from the cap cells and premature differentiation of GSCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Additionally, *zero population growth* (*zpg*), encoding a germline-specific gap junction is required for germ cell differentiation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Both diet and insulin-like signaling directly control GSC proliferation in *Drosophila melanogaster*.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Increasing levels of *Drosophila* insulin-like peptide (DILP) through diet results in increased GSC proliferation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Up-regulation of DILPs in aged GSCs and their niche results in increased maintenance and proliferation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] It has also been shown that DILPs regulate cap cell quantities and regulate the physical attachment of GSCs to cap cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] There are two possible mechanisms for stem cell renewal, symmetrical GSC division or de-differentiation of cystoblasts.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Normally, GSCs will divide asymmetrically to produce one daughter cystoblast, but it has been proposed that symmetrical division could result in the two daughter cells remaining GSCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] If GSCs are ablated to create an empty niche and the cap cells are still present and sending maintenance signals, differentiated cystoblasts can be recruited to the niche and de-differentiate into functional GSCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] As the *Drosophila* female ages, the stem cell niche undergoes age-dependent loss of GSC presence and activity.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] These losses are thought to be caused in part by degradation of the important signaling factors from the niche that maintains GSCs and their activity.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Progressive decline in GSC activity contributes to the observed reduction in fecundity of *Drosophila melanogaster* at old age; this decline in GSC activity can be partially attributed to a reduction of signaling pathway activity in the GSC niche.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] It has been found that there is a reduction in Dpp and Gbb signaling through aging.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] In addition to a reduction in niche signaling pathway activity, GSCs age cell-autonomously.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] In addition to studying the decline of signals coming from the niche, GSCs age intrinsically; there is age-dependent reduction of adhesion of GSCs to the cap cells and there is accumulation of reactive oxygen species (ROS) resulting in cellular damage which contributes to GSC aging.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] There is an observed reduction in the number of cap cells and the physical attachment of GSCs to cap cells through aging.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] *Shg* is expressed at significantly lower levels in an old GSC niche in comparison to a young one.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Males of *Drosophila melanogaster* each have two testes – long, tubular, coiled structures – and at the anterior most tip of each lies the GSC niche.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The testis GSC niche is built around a population of non-mitotic hub cells (a.k.a. niche cells), to which two populations of stem cells adhere: the GSCs and the somatic stem cells (SSCs, a.k.a. somatic cyst stem cells/cyst stem cells).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Each GSC is enclosed by a pair of SSCs, though each stem cell type is still in contact with the hub cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] In this way, the stem cell niche consists of these three cell types, as not only do the hub cells regulate GSC and SSC behaviour, but the stem cells also regulate the activity of each other.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The *Drosophila* testis GSC niche has proven a valuable model system for examining a wide range of cellular processes and signalling pathways.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The process of spermatogenesis begins when the GSCs divide asymmetrically, producing a GSC that maintains hub contact, and a gonialblast that exits the niche.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The SSCs divide with their GSC partner, and their non-mitotic progeny, the somatic cyst cells (SCCs, a.k.a. cyst cells) will enclose the gonialblast.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The gonialblast then undergoes four rounds of synchronous, transit-amplifying divisions with incomplete cytokinesis to produce a sixteen-cell spermatogonial cyst.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] This spermatogonial cyst then differentiates and grows into a spermatocyte, which will eventually undergo meiosis and produce sperm.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The two main molecular signalling pathways regulating stem cell behaviour in the testis GSC niche are the Jak-STAT and BMP signalling pathways.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Jak-STAT signalling originates in the hub cells, where the ligand Upd is secreted to the GSCs and SSCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] This leads to activation of the *Drosophila* STAT, Stat92E, a transcription factor which effects GSC adhesion to the hub cells, and SSC self-renewal via Zfh-1.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Jak-STAT signalling also influences the activation of BMP signalling, via the ligands Dpp and Gbb.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] These ligands are secreted into the GSCs from the SSCs and hub cells, activate BMP signalling, and suppress the expression of Bam, a differentiation factor.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Outside of the niche, gonialblasts no longer receive BMP ligands, and are free to begin their differentiation program.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Other important signalling pathways include the MAPK and Hedgehog, which regulate germline enclosure and somatic cell self-renewal, respectively.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The murine GSC niche in males, also called spermatogonial stem cell (SSC) niche, is located in the basal region of seminiferous tubules in the testes.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The seminiferous epithelium is composed of sertoli cells that are in contact with the basement membrane of the tubules, which separates the sertoli cells from the interstitial tissue below.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] This interstitial tissue comprises Leydig cells, macrophages, mesenchymal cells, capillary networks, and nerves.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] During development, primordial germ cells migrate into the seminiferous tubules and downward towards the basement membrane whilst remaining attached to the sertoli cells where they will subsequently differentiate into SSCs, also referred to as Asingle spermatogonia.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] These SSCs can either self-renew or commit to differentiating into spermatozoa upon the proliferation of Asingle into Apaired spermatogonia.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The 2 cells of Apaired spermatogonia remain attached by intercellular bridges and subsequently divide into Aaligned spermatogonia, which is made up of 4–16 connected cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Aaligned spermatogonia then undergo meiosis I to form spermatocytes and meiosis II to form spermatids which will mature into spermatozoa.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] This differentiation occurs along the longitudinal axis of sertoli cells, from the basement membrane to the apical lumen of the seminiferous tubules.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] However, sertoli cells form tight junctions that separate SSCs and spermatogonia in contact with the basement membrane from the spermatocytes and spermatids to create a basal and an adluminal compartment, whereby differentiating spermatocytes must traverse the tight junctions.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] These tight junctions form the blood testis barrier (BTB) and have been suggested to play a role in isolating differentiated cells in the adluminal compartment from secreted factors by the interstitial tissue and vasculature neighboring the basal compartment.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] E cadherin expression on SSCs in mice, unlike in *Drosophila*, have been shown to be dispensable as the transplantation of cultured SSCs lacking E-cadherin are able to colonize host seminiferous tubules and undergo spermatogenesis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] In addition the blood testis barrier provides architectural support and is composed of tight junction components such as occludins, claudins and zonula occludens (ZOs) which show dynamic expression during spermatogenesis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] For example, claudin 11 has been shown to be a necessary component of these tight junctions as mice lacking this gene have a defective blood testis barrier and do not produce mature spermatozoa.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] GDNF (Glial cell-derived neurotrophic factor) is known to stimulate self-renewal of SSCs and is secreted by the sertoli cells under the influence of gonadotropin FSH.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] GDNF is a related member of the TGFβ superfamily of growth factors and when overexpressed in mice, an increase in undifferentiated spermatogonia was observed which led to the formation of germ tumours.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] In corroboration for its role as a renewal factor, heterozygous knockout male mice for GDNF show decreased spermatogenesis that eventually leads to infertility.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] In addition the supplementation of GDNF has been shown to extend the expansion of mouse SSCs in culture.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] However, the GDNF receptor c-RET and co-receptor GFRa1 are not solely expressed on the SSCs but also on Apaired and Aaligned, therefore showing that GDNF is a renewal factor for Asingle to Aaligned in general rather than being specific to the Asingle SSC population.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] FGF2 (Fibroblast growth factor −2), secreted by sertoli cells, has also been shown to influence the renewal of SSCs and undifferentiated spermatogonia in a similar manner to GDNF.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Although sertoli cells appear to play a major role in renewal, it expresses receptors for testosterone that is secreted by Leydig cells whereas germ cells do not contain this receptor- thus alluding to an important role of Leydig cells upstream in mediating renewal.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Leydig cells also produce CSF 1 (Colony stimulating factor −1) for which SSCs strongly express the receptor CSF1R.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] When CSF 1 was added in culture with GDNF and FGF2 no further increase in proliferation was observed, however, the longer the germ cells remained in culture with CSF-1 the greater the SSC density observed when these germ cells were transplanted into host seminiferous tubules.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] This showed CSF 1 to be a specific renewal factor that tilts the SSCs towards renewal over differentiation, rather than affecting proliferation of SSCs and spermatogonia.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] GDNF, FGF 2 and CSF 1 have also been shown to influence self-renewal of stem cells in other mammalian tissues.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Plzf (Promyelocytic leukaemia zinc finger) has also been implicated in regulating SSC self-renewal and is expressed by Asingle, Apaired and Aaligned spermatogonia.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Plzf directly inhibits the transcription of a receptor, c-kit, in these early spermatogonia.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] However, its absence in late spermatogonia permits c-kit expression, which is subsequently activated by its ligand SCF (stem cell factor) secreted by sertoli cells, resulting in further differentiation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Also, the addition of BMP4 and Activin-A have shown to reduce self-renewal of SSCs in culture and increase stem cell differentiation, with BMP4 shown to increase the expression of c-kit.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Prolonged spermatogenesis relies on the maintenance of SSCs, however, this maintenance declines with age and leads to infertility.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Mice between 12 and 14 months of age show decreased testis weight, reduced spermatogenesis and SSC content.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Although stem cells are regarded as having the potential to infinitely replicate in vitro, factors provided by the niche are crucial in vivo.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Indeed, serial transplantation of SSCs from male mice of different ages into young mice 3 months of age, whose endogenous spermatogenesis had been ablated, was used to estimate stem cell content given that each stem cell would generate a colony of spermatogenesis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The results of this experiment showed that transplanted SSCs could be maintained far longer than their replicative lifespan for their age.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] In addition, a study also showed that SSCs from young fertile mice could not be maintained nor undergo spermatogenesis when transplanted into testes of old, infertile mice.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Together, these results points towards a deterioration of the SSC niche itself with aging rather than the loss of intrinsic factors in the SSC.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The hair follicle stem cell niche is one of the more closely studied niches thanks to its relative accessibility and role in important diseases such as melanoma.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The bulge area at the junction of arrector pili muscle to the hair follicle sheath has been shown to host the skin stem cells which can contribute to all epithelial skin layers.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] There cells are maintained by signaling in concert with niche cells – signals include paracrine (e.g. sonic hedgehog), autocrine and juxtacrine signals.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The bulge region of the hair follicle relies on these signals to maintain the stemness of the cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Fate mapping or cell lineage tracing has shown that Keratin 15 positive stem cells' progeny participate in all epithelial lineages.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The follicle undergoes cyclic regeneration in which these stem cells migrate to various regions and differentiate into the appropriate epithelial cell type.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Some important signals in the hair follicle stem cell niche produced by the mesenchymal dermal papilla or the bulge include BMP, TGF-β and Fibroblast growth factor (FGF) ligands and Wnt inhibitors.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] While, Wnt signaling pathways and β-catenin are important for stem cell maintenance, over-expression of β-catenin in hair follicles induces improper hair growth.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Therefore, these signals such as Wnt inhibitors produced by surrounding cells are important to maintain and facilitate the stem cell niche.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Intestinal organoids have been used to study intestinal stem cell niches.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] An intestinal organoid culture can be used to indirectly assess the effect of the manipulation on the stem cells through assessing the organoid's survival and growth.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Research using intestinal organoids have demonstrated that the survival of intestinal stem cells is improved by the presence of neurons and fibroblasts, and through the administration of IL-22.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Cardiovascular stem cell niches can be found within the right ventricular free wall, atria and outflow tracks of the heart.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] They are composed of Isl1+/Flk1+ cardiac progenitor cells (CPCs) that are localized into discrete clusters within a ColIV and laminin extracellular matrix (ECM).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] ColI and fibronectin are predominantly found outside the CPC clusters within the myocardium.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Immunohistochemical staining has been used to demonstrate that differentiating CPCs, which migrate away from the progenitor clusters and into the ColI and fibronectin ECM surrounding the niche, down-regulate Isl1 while up-regulating mature cardiac markers such as troponin C.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] There is a current controversy over the role of Isl1+ cells in the cardiovascular system.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The role of these cells and their niche are under intense research and debate.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Neural stem cell niches are divided in two : the Subependymal zone (SEZ) and the Subgranular zone (SGZ).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The SEZ is a thin area beneath the ependymal cell layer that contains three types of neural stem cells : infrequently dividing neural stem cells (NSCs), rapidly dividing transit amplifying precursors (TaPs) and neuroblasts (NBs).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The SEZ extracellular matrix (**ECM**) has significant differences in composition compared to surrounding tissues.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Recently, it was described that progenitor cells, NSCs, TaPs and NBs were attached to ECM structures called Fractones.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] These structures are rich in laminin, collagen and heparan sulfate proteoglycans.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Other ECM molecules, such as tenascin-C, MMPs and different proteoglycans are also implicated in the neural stem cell niche.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Cancer tissue is morphologically heterogenous, not only due to the variety of cell types present, endothelial, fibroblast and various immune cells, but cancer cells themselves are not a homogenous population either.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] In accordance with the hierarchy model of tumours, the cancer stem cells (CSC) are maintained by biochemical and physical contextual signals emanating from the microenvironment, called the cancer stem cell niche.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The CSC niche is very similar to normal stem cells niche (embryonic stem cell (ESC), Adult Stem Cell ASC) in function (maintaining of self-renewal, undifferentiated state and ability to differentiate) and in signalling pathways (Activin/Noda, Akt/PTEN, JAK/STAT, PI3-K, TGF-β, Wnt and BMP).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] It is hypothesized that CSCs arise form aberrant signalling of the microenvironment and participates not only in providing survival signals to CSCs but also in metastasis by induction of epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Hypoxic condition in stem cell niches (ESC, ASC or CSC) is necessary for maintaining stem cells in an undifferentiated state and also for minimizing DNA damage via oxidation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The maintaining of the hypoxic state is under control of Hypoxia-Inducible transcription Factors (HIFs).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] HIFs contribute to tumour progression, cell survival and metastasis by regulation of target genes as VEGF, GLUT-1, ADAM-1, Oct4 and Notch.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Hypoxia plays an important role in the regulation of cancer stem cell niches and EMT through the promotion of HIFs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] These HIFs help maintain cancer stem cell niches by regulating important stemness genes such as Oct4, Nanog, SOX2, Klf4, and cMyc.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] HIFs also regulate important tumor suppressor genes such as p53 and genes that promote metastasis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Although HIFs increase the survival of cells by decreasing the effects of oxidative stress, they have also been shown to decrease factors such as RAD51 and H2AX that maintain genomic stability.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] In the hypoxic condition there is an increase of intracellular Reactive Oxygen Species (ROS) which also promote CSCs survival via stress response.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] ROS stabilizes HIF-1α which promotes the Met proto-oncogene, which drives metastasis or motogenic escape in melanoma cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] All of these factors contribute to a cancer stem cell phenotype which is why it is often referred to as a hypoxic stem cell niche.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Hypoxic environments are often found in tumors where the cells are dividing faster that angiogenesis can occur.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] It is important to study hypoxia as an aspect of cancer because hypoxic environments have been shown to be resistant to radiation therapy.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Radiation has been shown to increase the amounts of HIF-1.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] EMT induction by hypoxia though interactions between HIF-1α and ROS is crucial for metastasis in cancers such as melanoma.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] It has been found that many genes associated with melanoma are regulated by hypoxia such as MXI1, FN1, and NME1.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Epithelial–mesenchymal transition is a morphogenetic process, normally occurs in embryogenesis that is "hijacked" by cancer stem cells by detaching from their primary place and migrating to another one.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The dissemination is followed by reverse transition so-called Epithelial-Mesenchymal Transition (EMT).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] This process is regulated by CSCs microenvironment via the same signalling pathways as in embryogenesis using the growth factors (TGF-β, PDGF, EGF), cytokine IL-8 and extracellular matrix components.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] These growth factors' interactions through intracellular signal transducers like β-catenin has been shown to induce metastatic potential.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] A characteristic of EMT is loss of the epithelial markers (E-cadherin, cytokeratins, claudin, occluding, desmoglein, desmocolin) and gain of mesenchymal markers (N-cadherin, vimentin, fibronectin).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] There is also certain degree of similarity in homing-mobilization of normal stem cells and metastasis-invasion of cancer stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The next sharing molecule is Stromal cell-Derived Factor-1 (SDF-1).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The EMT and cancer progression can be triggered also by chronic inflammation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The main roles have molecules (IL-6, IL-8, TNF-α, NFκB, TGF-β, HIF-1α) which can regulate both processes through regulation of downstream signalling that overlapping between EMT and inflammation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The downstream pathways involving in regulation of CSCs are Wnt, SHH, Notch, TGF-β, RTKs-EGF, FGF, IGF, HGF.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] NFκB regulates the EMT, migration and invasion of CSCs through Slug, Snail and Twist.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The activation of NFκB leads to increase not only in production of IL-6, TNF-α and SDF-1 but also in delivery of growth factors.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The source of the cytokine production are lymphocytes (TNF-α), Mesenchymal Stem Cells (SDF-1, IL-6, IL8).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Interleukin 6 mediates activation of STAT3.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The high level of STAT3 was described in isolated CSCs from liver, bone, cervical and brain cancer.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The inhibition of STAT3 results in dramatic reduction in their formation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Generally IL-6 contributes a survival advantage to local stem cells and thus facilitates tumorigenesis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] SDF-1α secreted from Mesenchymal Stem Cells (MSCs) has important role in homing and maintenance of Hematopoietic Stem Cell (HSC) in bone marrow niche but also in homing and dissemination of CSC.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Hypoxia is a main stimulant for angiogenesis, with HIF-1α being the primary mediator.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Angiogenesis induced by hypoxic conditions is called an "Angiogenic switch".
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] HIF-1 promotes expression of several angiogenic factors: Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor (VEGF), basic Fibroblast Growth Factor (bFGF), Placenta-Like Growth Factor (PLGF), Platelet-Derived Growth Factor (PDGF) and Epidermal Growth Factor.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] But there is evidence that the expression of angiogenic agens by cancer cells can also be HIF-1 independent.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] It seems that there is an important role of Ras protein, and that intracellular levels of calcium regulate the expression of angiogenic genes in response to hypoxia.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] The angiogenic switch downregulates angiogenesis suppressor proteins, such as thrombospondin, angiostatin, endostatin and tumstatin.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Angiogenesis is necessary for the primary tumour growth.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] During injury, support cells are able to activate a program for repair, recapitulating aspects of development in the area of damage.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] These areas become permissive for stem cell renewal, migration and differentiation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] For instance in the CNS, injury is able to activate a developmental program in astrocytes that allow them to express molecules that support stem cells such as chemokines i.e.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] SDF-1 and morphogens such as sonic hedgehog.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] It is evident that biophysio-chemical characteristics of ECM such as composition, shape, topography, stiffness, and mechanical strength can control the stem cell behavior.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] These ECM factors are equally important when stem cells are grown in vitro.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] Given a choice between niche cell-stem cell interaction and ECM-stem cell interaction, mimicking ECM is preferred as that can be precisely controlled by scaffold fabrication techniques, processing parameters or post-fabrication modifications.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell-niche] In order to mimic, it is essential to understand natural properties of ECM and their role in stem cell fate processes.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In multicellular organisms, **stem cells** are undifferentiated or partially differentiated cells that can change into various types of cells and proliferate indefinitely to produce more of the same stem cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] They are the earliest type of cell in a cell lineage.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] They are found in both embryonic and adult organisms, but they have slightly different properties in each.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] They are usually distinguished from progenitor cells, which cannot divide indefinitely, and precursor or blast cells, which are usually committed to differentiating into one cell type.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In mammals, roughly 50 to 150 cells make up the inner cell mass during the blastocyst stage of embryonic development, around days 5–14.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] *In vivo*, they eventually differentiate into all of the body's cell types (making them pluripotent).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] This process starts with the differentiation into the three germ layers – the ectoderm, mesoderm and endoderm – at the gastrulation stage.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] However, when they are isolated and cultured *in vitro*, they can be kept in the stem-cell stage and are known as embryonic stem cells (ESCs).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Adult stem cells are found in a few select locations in the body, known as niches, such as those in the bone marrow or gonads.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] They exist to replenish rapidly lost cell types and are multipotent or unipotent, meaning they only differentiate into a few cell types or one type of cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In mammals, they include, among others, hematopoietic stem cells, which replenish blood and immune cells, basal cells, which maintain the skin epithelium, and mesenchymal stem cells, which maintain bone, cartilage, muscle and fat cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Adult stem cells are a small minority of cells; they are vastly outnumbered by the progenitor cells and terminally differentiated cells that they differentiate into.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Research into stem cells grew out of findings by Canadian biologists Ernest McCulloch, James Till and Andrew J.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Becker at the University of Toronto and the Ontario Cancer Institute in the 1960s.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] As of 2016, the only established medical therapy using stem cells is hematopoietic stem cell transplantation, first performed in 1958 by French oncologist Georges Mathé.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Since 1998 however, it has been possible to culture and differentiate human embryonic stem cells (in stem-cell lines).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The process of isolating these cells has been controversial, because it typically results in the destruction of the embryo.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Sources for isolating ESCs have been restricted in some European countries and Canada, but others such as the UK and China have promoted the research.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Somatic cell nuclear transfer is a cloning method that can be used to create a cloned embryo for the use of its embryonic stem cells in stem cell therapy.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In 2006, a Japanese team led by Shinya Yamanaka discovered a method to convert mature body cells back into stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] These were termed induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The term *stem cell* was coined by Theodor Boveri and Valentin Haecker in the late 19th century.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Pioneering works in theory of blood stem cell were conducted at the beginning of the 20th century by Artur Pappenheim, Alexander A.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The key properties of a stem cell were first defined by Ernest McCulloch and James Till at the University of Toronto's Faculty of Medicine and the Ontario Cancer Institute in the early 1960s.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] They discovered the blood-forming stem cell, the hematopoietic stem cell (HSC), through their pioneering work in mice.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] McCulloch and Till began a series of experiments in which bone marrow cells were injected into irradiated mice.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] They observed lumps in the spleens of the mice that were linearly proportional to the number of bone marrow cells injected.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] They hypothesized that each lump (colony) was a clone arising from a single marrow cell (stem cell).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In subsequent work, McCulloch and Till, joined by graduate student Andrew John Becker and senior scientist Louis Siminovitch, confirmed that each lump did in fact arise from a single cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Their results were published in *Nature* in 1963.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In that same year, Siminovitch was a lead investigator for studies that found colony-forming cells were capable of self-renewal, which is a key defining property of stem cells that Till and McCulloch had theorized.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The first therapy using stem cells was a bone marrow transplant performed by French oncologist Georges Mathé in 1956 on five workers at the Vinča Nuclear Institute in Yugoslavia who had been affected by a criticality accident.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In 1981, embryonic stem (ES) cells were first isolated and successfully cultured using mouse blastocysts by British biologists Martin Evans and Matthew Kaufman.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] This allowed the formation of murine genetic models, a system in which the genes of mice are deleted or altered in order to study their function in pathology.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In 1991, a process that allowed the human stem cell to be isolated was patented by Ann Tsukamoto.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] By 1998, human embryonic stem cells were first isolated by American biologist James Thomson, which made it possible to have new transplantation methods or various cell types for testing new treatments.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In 2006, Shinya Yamanaka's team in Kyoto, Japan converted fibroblasts into pluripotent stem cells by modifying the expression of only four genes.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The feat represents the origin of induced pluripotent stem cells, known as iPS cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In 2011, a female maned wolf, run over by a truck, underwent stem cell treatment at the Zoo Brasília, this being the first recorded case of the use of stem cells to heal injuries in a wild animal.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] When a stem cell self-renews, it divides and disrupts the undifferentiated state.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] This self-renewal demands control of cell cycle as well as upkeep of multipotency or pluripotency, which all depends on the stem cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Stem cells use telomerase, a protein that restores telomeres, to protect their DNA and extend their cell division limit (the Hayflick limit).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Potency specifies the differentiation potential (the potential to differentiate into different cell types) of the stem cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In practice, stem cells are identified by whether they can regenerate tissue.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] For example, the defining test for bone marrow or hematopoietic stem cells (HSCs) is the ability to transplant the cells and save an individual without HSCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] This demonstrates that the cells can produce new blood cells over a long term.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] It should also be possible to isolate stem cells from the transplanted individual, which can themselves be transplanted into another individual without HSCs, demonstrating that the stem cell was able to self-renew.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Properties of stem cells can be illustrated *in vitro*, using methods such as clonogenic assays, in which single cells are assessed for their ability to differentiate and self-renew.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Stem cells can also be isolated by their possession of a distinctive set of cell surface markers.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] However, *in vitro* culture conditions can alter the behavior of cells, making it unclear whether the cells shall behave in a similar manner *in vivo*.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] There is considerable debate as to whether some proposed adult cell populations are truly stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Embryonic stem cells (ESCs) are the cells of the inner cell mass of a blastocyst, formed prior to implantation in the uterus.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In human embryonic development the blastocyst stage is reached 4–5 days after fertilization, at which time it consists of 50–150 cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] ESCs are pluripotent and give rise during development to all derivatives of the three germ layers: ectoderm, endoderm and mesoderm.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In other words, they can develop into each of the more than 200 cell types of the adult body when given sufficient and necessary stimulation for a specific cell type.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] They do not contribute to the extraembryonic membranes or to the placenta.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] During embryonic development the cells of the inner cell mass continuously divide and become more specialized.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] For example, a portion of the ectoderm in the dorsal part of the embryo specializes as 'neurectoderm', which will become the future central nervous system (CNS).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Later in development, neurulation causes the neurectoderm to form the neural tube.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] At the neural tube stage, the anterior portion undergoes encephalization to generate or 'pattern' the basic form of the brain.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] At this stage of development, the principal cell type of the CNS is considered a neural stem cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The neural stem cells self-renew and at some point transition into radial glial progenitor cells (RGPs).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Early-formed RGPs self-renew by symmetrical division to form a reservoir group of progenitor cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] These cells transition to a neurogenic state and start to divide asymmetrically to produce a large diversity of many different neuron types, each with unique gene expression, morphological, and functional characteristics.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The process of generating neurons from radial glial cells is called neurogenesis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The radial glial cell, has a distinctive bipolar morphology with highly elongated processes spanning the thickness of the neural tube wall.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] It shares some glial characteristics, most notably the expression of glial fibrillary acidic protein (GFAP).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The radial glial cell is the primary neural stem cell of the developing vertebrate CNS, and its cell body resides in the ventricular zone, adjacent to the developing ventricular system.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Neural stem cells are committed to the neuronal lineages (neurons, astrocytes, and oligodendrocytes), and thus their potency is restricted.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Nearly all research to date has made use of mouse embryonic stem cells (mES) or human embryonic stem cells (hES) derived from the early inner cell mass.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Both have the essential stem cell characteristics, yet they require very different environments in order to maintain an undifferentiated state.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Mouse ES cells are grown on a layer of gelatin as an extracellular matrix (for support) and require the presence of leukemia inhibitory factor (LIF) in serum media.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] A drug cocktail containing inhibitors to GSK3B and the MAPK/ERK pathway, called 2i, has also been shown to maintain pluripotency in stem cell culture.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Human ESCs are grown on a feeder layer of mouse embryonic fibroblasts and require the presence of basic fibroblast growth factor (bFGF or FGF-2).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Without optimal culture conditions or genetic manipulation, embryonic stem cells will rapidly differentiate.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] A human embryonic stem cell is also defined by the expression of several transcription factors and cell surface proteins.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The transcription factors Oct-4, Nanog, and Sox2 form the core regulatory network that ensures the suppression of genes that lead to differentiation and the maintenance of pluripotency.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The cell surface antigens most commonly used to identify hES cells are the glycolipids stage specific embryonic antigen 3 and 4, and the keratan sulfate antigens Tra-1-60 and Tra-1-81.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The molecular definition of a stem cell includes many more proteins and continues to be a topic of research.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] By using human embryonic stem cells to produce specialized cells like nerve cells or heart cells in the lab, scientists can gain access to adult human cells without taking tissue from patients.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] They can then study these specialized adult cells in detail to try to discern complications of diseases, or to study cell reactions to proposed new drugs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Because of their combined abilities of unlimited expansion and pluripotency, embryonic stem cells remain a theoretically potential source for regenerative medicine and tissue replacement after injury or disease.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] However, there are currently no approved treatments using ES cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The first human trial was approved by the US Food and Drug Administration in January 2009.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] However, the human trial was not initiated until October 13, 2010, in Atlanta for spinal cord injury research.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] On November 14, 2011, the company conducting the trial (Geron Corporation) announced that it will discontinue further development of its stem cell programs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Differentiating ES cells into usable cells while avoiding transplant rejection are just a few of the hurdles that embryonic stem cell researchers still face.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Embryonic stem cells, being pluripotent, require specific signals for correct differentiation – if injected directly into another body, ES cells will differentiate into many different types of cells, causing a teratoma.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Many nations currently have moratoria or limitations on either human ES cell research or the production of new human ES cell lines due to their ethical controversies.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The use of embryonic stem cells has generated significant ethical and political controversy.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Central to the debate is the moral status of the human embryo, as deriving ES typically involves the destruction of early-stage embryos.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Critics argue that this practice violates the sanctity of human life, and therefore is unacceptable.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Mesenchymal stem cells (MSC) or mesenchymal stromal cells, also known as medicinal signaling cells are known to be multipotent, which can be found in adult tissues, for example, in the muscle, liver, bone marrow and adipose tissue.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Mesenchymal stem cells usually function as structural support in various organs as mentioned above, and control the movement of substances.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] MSC can differentiate into numerous cell categories as an illustration of adipocytes, osteocytes, and chondrocytes, derived by the mesodermal layer.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Where the mesoderm layer provides an increase to the body's skeletal elements, such as relating to the cartilage or bone.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The term "meso" means middle, infusion originated from the Greek, signifying that mesenchymal cells are able to range and travel in early embryonic growth among the ectodermal and endodermal layers.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] This mechanism helps with space-filling thus, key for repairing wounds in adult organisms that have to do with mesenchymal cells in the dermis (skin), bone, or muscle.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Mesenchymal stem cells are known to be essential for regenerative medicine.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] They are broadly studied in clinical trials.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Since they are easily isolated and obtain high yield, high plasticity, which makes able to facilitate inflammation and encourage cell growth, cell differentiation, and restoring tissue derived from immunomodulation and immunosuppression.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] MSC comes from the bone marrow, which requires an aggressive procedure when it comes to isolating the quantity and quality of the isolated cell, and it varies by how old the donor.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] When comparing the rates of MSC in the bone marrow aspirates and bone marrow stroma, the aspirates tend to have lower rates of MSC than the stroma.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] MSC are known to be heterogeneous, and they express a high level of pluripotent markers when compared to other types of stem cells, such as embryonic stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] MSCs injection leads to wound healing primarily through stimulation of angiogenesis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Embryonic stem cells (ESCs) have the ability to divide indefinitely while keeping their pluripotency, which is made possible through specialized mechanisms of cell cycle control.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Compared to proliferating somatic cells, ESCs have unique cell cycle characteristics—such as rapid cell division caused by shortened G1 phase, absent G0 phase, and modifications in cell cycle checkpoints—which leaves the cells mostly in S phase at any given time.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] ESCs' rapid division is demonstrated by their short doubling time, which ranges from 8 to 10 hours, whereas somatic cells have doubling time of approximately 20 hours or longer.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] As cells differentiate, these properties change: G1 and G2 phases lengthen, leading to longer cell division cycles.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] This suggests that a specific cell cycle structure may contribute to the establishment of pluripotency.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Particularly because G1 phase is the phase in which cells have increased sensitivity to differentiation, shortened G1 is one of the key characteristics of ESCs and plays an important role in maintaining undifferentiated phenotype.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Although the exact molecular mechanism remains only partially understood, several studies have shown insight on how ESCs progress through G1—and potentially other phases—so rapidly.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The cell cycle is regulated by complex network of cyclins, cyclin-dependent kinases (Cdk), cyclin-dependent kinase inhibitors (Cdkn), pocket proteins of the retinoblastoma (Rb) family, and other accessory factors.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Foundational insight into the distinctive regulation of ESC cell cycle was gained by studies on mouse ESCs (mESCs). mESCs showed a cell cycle with highly abbreviated G1 phase, which enabled cells to rapidly alternate between M phase and S phase.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] However, in mESCs, this typically ordered and oscillatory activity of Cyclin-Cdk complexes is absent.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Rather, the Cyclin E/Cdk2 complex is constitutively active throughout the cycle, keeping retinoblastoma protein (pRb) hyperphosphorylated and thus inactive.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] This allows for direct transition from M phase to the late G1 phase, leading to absence of D-type cyclins and therefore a shortened G1 phase.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Cdk2 activity is crucial for both cell cycle regulation and cell-fate decisions in mESCs; downregulation of Cdk2 activity prolongs G1 phase progression, establishes a somatic cell-like cell cycle, and induces expression of differentiation markers.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In human ESCs (hESCs), the duration of G1 is dramatically shortened.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] This has been attributed to high mRNA levels of G1-related Cyclin D2 and Cdk4 genes and low levels of cell cycle regulatory proteins that inhibit cell cycle progression at G1, such as p21CipP1, p27Kip1, and p57Kip2.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Furthermore, regulators of Cdk4 and Cdk6 activity, such as members of the Ink family of inhibitors (p15, p16, p18, and p19), are expressed at low levels or not at all.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Thus, similar to mESCs, hESCs show high Cdk activity, with Cdk2 exhibiting the highest kinase activity.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Also similar to mESCs, hESCs demonstrate the importance of Cdk2 in G1 phase regulation by showing that G1 to S transition is delayed when Cdk2 activity is inhibited and G1 is arrest when Cdk2 is knocked down.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] However unlike mESCs, hESCs have a functional G1 phase. hESCs show that the activities of Cyclin E/Cdk2 and Cyclin A/Cdk2 complexes are cell cycle-dependent and the Rb checkpoint in G1 is functional.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] ESCs are also characterized by G1 checkpoint non-functionality, even though the G1 checkpoint is crucial for maintaining genomic stability.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In response to DNA damage, ESCs do not stop in G1 to repair DNA damages but instead, depend on S and G2/M checkpoints or undergo apoptosis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The absence of G1 checkpoint in ESCs allows for the removal of cells with damaged DNA, hence avoiding potential mutations from inaccurate DNA repair.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Consistent with this idea, ESCs are hypersensitive to DNA damage to minimize mutations passed onto the next generation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The primitive stem cells located in the organs of fetuses are referred to as fetal stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Extraembryonic fetal stem cells come from extraembryonic membranes, and are generally not distinguished from adult stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] These stem cells are acquired after birth, they are not immortal but have a high level of cell division, and are pluripotent.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Adult stem cells, also called somatic (from Greek σωματικóς, "of the body") stem cells, are stem cells which maintain and repair the tissue in which they are found.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Adipose tissue (fat cells), which requires extraction by liposuction.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Blood, which requires extraction through apheresis, wherein blood is drawn from the donor (similar to a blood donation), and passed through a machine that extracts the stem cells and returns other portions of the blood to the donor.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Stem cells can also be taken from umbilical cord blood just after birth.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Of all stem cell types, autologous harvesting involves the least risk.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] By definition, autologous cells are obtained from one's own body, just as one may bank their own blood for elective surgical procedures.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Pluripotent adult stem cells are rare and generally small in number, but they can be found in umbilical cord blood and other tissues.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Bone marrow is a rich source of adult stem cells, which have been used in treating several conditions including liver cirrhosis, chronic limb ischemia and endstage heart failure.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The quantity of bone marrow stem cells declines with age and is greater in males than females during reproductive years.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Much adult stem cell research to date has aimed to characterize their potency and self-renewal capabilities.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] DNA damage accumulates with age in both stem cells and the cells that comprise the stem cell environment.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] This accumulation is considered to be responsible, at least in part, for increasing stem cell dysfunction with aging (see DNA damage theory of aging).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Most adult stem cells are lineage-restricted (multipotent) and are generally referred to by their tissue origin (mesenchymal stem cell, adipose-derived stem cell, endothelial stem cell, dental pulp stem cell, etc.).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Muse cells (multi-lineage differentiating stress enduring cells) are a recently discovered pluripotent stem cell type found in multiple adult tissues, including adipose, dermal fibroblasts, and bone marrow.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] While rare, muse cells are identifiable by their expression of SSEA-3, a marker for undifferentiated stem cells, and general mesenchymal stem cells markers such as CD90, CD105.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] When subjected to single cell suspension culture, the cells will generate clusters that are similar to embryoid bodies in morphology as well as gene expression, including canonical pluripotency markers Oct4, Sox2, and Nanog.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Adult stem cell treatments have been successfully used for many years to treat leukemia and related bone/blood cancers through bone marrow transplants.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Adult stem cells are also used in veterinary medicine to treat tendon and ligament injuries in horses.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The use of adult stem cells in research and therapy is not as controversial as the use of embryonic stem cells, because the production of adult stem cells does not require the destruction of an embryo.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Additionally, in instances where adult stem cells are obtained from the intended recipient (an autograft), the risk of rejection is essentially non-existent.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Consequently, more US government funding is being provided for adult stem cell research.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Adult stem cells are known to have a limited lifespan in vitro and to enter replicative senescence almost undetectably upon starting in vitro culturing.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Hematopoietic stem cells (HSCs) are vulnerable to DNA damage and mutations that increase with age.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] This vulnerability may explain the increased risk of slow growing blood cancers (myeloid malignancies) in the elderly.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Several factors appear to influence HSC aging including responses to the production of reactive oxygen species that may cause DNA damage and genetic mutations as well as altered epigenetic profiling.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Also called perinatal stem cells, these multipotent stem cells are found in amniotic fluid and umbilical cord blood.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] These stem cells are very active, expand extensively without feeders and are not tumorigenic.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Amniotic stem cells are multipotent and can differentiate in cells of adipogenic, osteogenic, myogenic, endothelial, hepatic and also neuronal lines.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Amniotic stem cells are a topic of active research.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Use of stem cells from amniotic fluid overcomes the ethical objections to using human embryos as a source of cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Roman Catholic teaching forbids the use of embryonic stem cells in experimentation; accordingly, the Vatican newspaper "Osservatore Romano" called amniotic stem cells "the future of medicine".
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] It is possible to collect amniotic stem cells for donors or for autologous use: the first US amniotic stem cells bank was opened in 2009 in Medford, MA, by Biocell Center Corporation and collaborates with various hospitals and universities all over the world.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Adult stem cells have limitations with their potency; unlike embryonic stem cells (ESCs), they are not able to differentiate into cells from all three germ layers.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] However, reprogramming allows for the creation of pluripotent cells, induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSCs), from adult cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] These are not adult stem cells, but somatic cells (e.g. epithelial cells) reprogrammed to give rise to cells with pluripotent capabilities.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Using genetic reprogramming with protein transcription factors, pluripotent stem cells with ESC-like capabilities have been derived.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The first demonstration of induced pluripotent stem cells was conducted by Shinya Yamanaka and his colleagues at Kyoto University.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] They used the transcription factors Oct3/4, Sox2, c-Myc, and Klf4 to reprogram mouse fibroblast cells into pluripotent cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Subsequent work used these factors to induce pluripotency in human fibroblast cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Junying Yu, James Thomson, and their colleagues at the University of Wisconsin–Madison used a different set of factors, Oct4, Sox2, Nanog and Lin28, and carried out their experiments using cells from human foreskin.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] However, they were able to replicate Yamanaka's finding that inducing pluripotency in human cells was possible.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Induced pluripotent stem cells differ from embryonic stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] They share many similar properties, such as pluripotency and differentiation potential, the expression of pluripotency genes, epigenetic patterns, embryoid body and teratoma formation, and viable chimera formation, but there are many differences within these properties.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The chromatin of iPSCs appears to be more "closed" or methylated than that of ESCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Similarly, the gene expression pattern between ESCs and iPSCs, or even iPSCs sourced from different origins.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] There are thus questions about the "completeness" of reprogramming and the somatic memory of induced pluripotent stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Despite this, inducing somatic cells to be pluripotent appears to be viable.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] As a result of the success of these experiments, Ian Wilmut, who helped create the first cloned animal Dolly the Sheep, has announced that he will abandon somatic cell nuclear transfer as an avenue of research.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The ability to induce pluripotency benefits developments in tissue engineering.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] By providing a suitable scaffold and microenvironment, iPSC can be differentiated into cells of therapeutic application, and for *in vitro* models to study toxins and pathogenesis.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Induced pluripotent stem cells provide several therapeutic advantages.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] They thus have great differentiation potential; theoretically, they could produce any cell within the human body (if reprogramming to pluripotency was "complete").
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Moreover, unlike ESCs, they potentially could allow doctors to create a pluripotent stem cell line for each individual patient.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Frozen blood samples can be used as a valuable source of induced pluripotent stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Patient specific stem cells allow for the screening for side effects before drug treatment, as well as the reduced risk of transplantation rejection.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Despite their current limited use therapeutically, iPSCs hold great potential for future use in medical treatment and research.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The key factors controlling the cell cycle also regulate pluripotency.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Thus, manipulation of relevant genes can maintain pluripotency and reprogram somatic cells to an induced pluripotent state.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] However, reprogramming of somatic cells is often low in efficiency and considered stochastic.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] With the idea that a more rapid cell cycle is a key component of pluripotency, reprogramming efficiency can be improved.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Methods for improving pluripotency through manipulation of cell cycle regulators include: overexpression of Cyclin D/Cdk4, phosphorylation of Sox2 at S39 and S253, overexpression of Cyclin A and Cyclin E, knockdown of Rb, and knockdown of members of the Cip/Kip family or the Ink family.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Furthermore, reprogramming efficiency is correlated with the number of cell divisions happened during the stochastic phase, which is suggested by the growing inefficiency of reprogramming of older or slow diving cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Lineage is an important procedure to analyze developing embryos.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Since cell lineages shows the relationship between cells at each division.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] This helps in analyzing stem cell lineages along the way which helps recognize stem cell effectiveness, lifespan, and other factors.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] With the technique of cell lineage mutant genes can be analyzed in stem cell clones that can help in genetic pathways.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] These pathways can regulate how the stem cell perform.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Symmetric division gives rise to two identical daughter cells both endowed with stem cell properties.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Asymmetric division, on the other hand, produces only one stem cell and a progenitor cell with limited self-renewal potential.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Progenitors can go through several rounds of cell division before terminally differentiating into a mature cell.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] It is possible that the molecular distinction between symmetric and asymmetric divisions lies in differential segregation of cell membrane proteins (such as receptors) between the daughter cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] An alternative theory is that stem cells remain undifferentiated due to environmental cues in their particular niche.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Stem cells differentiate when they leave that niche or no longer receive those signals.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Studies in *Drosophila* germarium have identified the signals decapentaplegic and adherens junctions that prevent germarium stem cells from differentiating.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In the United States, Executive Order 13505 established that federal money can be used for research in which approved human embryonic stem-cell (hESC) lines are used, but it cannot be used to derive new lines.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The National Institutes of Health (NIH) Guidelines on Human Stem Cell Research, effective July 7, 2009, implemented the Executive Order 13505 by establishing criteria which hESC lines must meet to be approved for funding.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The NIH Human Embryonic Stem Cell Registry can be accessed online and has updated information on cell lines eligible for NIH funding.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] There are 486 approved lines as of January 2022.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Stem cell therapy is the use of stem cells to treat or prevent a disease or condition.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Bone marrow transplant is a form of stem cell therapy that has been used for many years because it has proven to be effective in clinical trials.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Stem cell implantation may help in strengthening the left-ventricle of the heart, as well as retaining the heart tissue to patients who have suffered from heart attacks in the past.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] For over 50 years, hematopoietic stem cell transplantation (HSCT) has been used to treat people with conditions such as leukaemia and lymphoma; this is the only widely practiced form of stem-cell therapy.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] As of 2016, the only established therapy using stem cells is hematopoietic stem cell transplantation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] This usually takes the form of a bone-marrow transplantation, but the cells can also be derived from umbilical cord blood.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Research is underway to develop various sources for stem cells as well as to apply stem-cell treatments for neurodegenerative diseases and conditions such as diabetes and heart disease.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Stem cell treatments may lower symptoms of the disease or condition that is being treated.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The lowering of symptoms may allow patients to reduce the drug intake of the disease or condition.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Stem cell treatment may also provide knowledge for society to further stem cell understanding and future treatments.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The physicians' creed would be to do no injury, and stem cells make that simpler than ever before.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Surgical processes by their character are harmful.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Tissue has to be dropped as a way to reach a successful outcome.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] One may prevent the dangers of surgical interventions using stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Additionally, there's a possibility of disease, and whether the procedure fails, further surgery may be required.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Risks associated with anesthesia can also be eliminated with stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] On top of that, stem cells have been harvested from the patient's body and redeployed in which they're wanted.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Since they come from the patient's own body, this is referred to as an autologous treatment.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Autologous remedies are thought to be the safest because there's likely zero probability of donor substance rejection.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Stem cell treatments may require immunosuppression because of a requirement for radiation before the transplant to remove the person's previous cells, or because the patient's immune system may target the stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] One approach to avoid the second possibility is to use stem cells from the same patient who is being treated.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Pluripotency in certain stem cells could also make it difficult to obtain a specific cell type.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] It is also difficult to obtain the exact cell type needed, because not all cells in a population differentiate uniformly.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Undifferentiated cells can create tissues other than desired types.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Some stem cells form tumors after transplantation; pluripotency is linked to tumor formation especially in embryonic stem cells, fetal proper stem cells, induced pluripotent stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Fetal proper stem cells form tumors despite multipotency.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Ethical concerns are also raised about the practice of using or researching embryonic stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Harvesting cells from the blastocyst results in the death of the blastocyst.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The concern is whether or not the blastocyst should be considered as a human life.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The debate on this issue is mainly a philosophical one, not a scientific one.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Stem cell tourism is the part of the medical tourism industry in which patients travel to obtain stem cell procedures.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The United States has had an explosion of "stem cell clinics".
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Stem cell procedures are highly profitable for clinics.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The advertising sounds authoritative but the efficacy and safety of the procedures is unproven.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Patients sometimes experience complications, such as spinal tumors and death.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The high expense can also lead to financial problems.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] According to researchers, there is a need to educate the public, patients, and doctors about this issue.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] According to the International Society for Stem Cell Research, the largest academic organization that advocates for stem cell research, stem cell therapies are under development and cannot yet be said to be proven.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Doctors should inform patients that clinical trials continue to investigate whether these therapies are safe and effective but that unethical clinics present them as proven.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Some of the fundamental patents covering human embryonic stem cells are owned by the Wisconsin Alumni Research Foundation (WARF) – they are patents 5,843,780, 6,200,806, and 7,029,913 invented by James A.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] WARF does not enforce these patents against academic scientists, but does enforce them against companies.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In 2006, a request for the US Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO) to re-examine the three patents was filed by the Public Patent Foundation on behalf of its client, the non-profit patent-watchdog group Consumer Watchdog (formerly the Foundation for Taxpayer and Consumer Rights).
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The decision on one of the patents (7,029,913) was appealable, while the decisions on the other two were not.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Consumer Watchdog appealed the granting of the '913 patent to the USPTO's Board of Patent Appeals and Interferences (BPAI) which granted the appeal, and in 2010 the BPAI decided that the amended claims of the '913 patent were not patentable.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] However, WARF was able to re-open prosecution of the case and did so, amending the claims of the '913 patent again to make them more narrow, and in January 2013 the amended claims were allowed.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In July 2013, Consumer Watchdog announced that it would appeal the decision to allow the claims of the '913 patent to the US Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit (CAFC), the federal appeals court that hears patent cases.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] At a hearing in December 2013, the CAFC raised the question of whether Consumer Watchdog had legal standing to appeal; the case could not proceed until that issue was resolved.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Research is underway to develop various sources for stem cells.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Research is attempting to generating organoids using stem cells, which would allow for further understanding of human development, organogenesis, and modeling of human diseases.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Engineered 'synthetic organizer' (SO) cells can instruct stem cells to grow into specific tissues and organs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The program used native and synthetic cell adhesion protein molecules (CAMs) that help make cells sticky.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The organizer cells self-assembled around mouse ESCs.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] These cells were engineered to produce morphogens (signaling molecules) that direct cellular development based on their concentration.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] Delivered morphogens disperse, leaving higher concentrations closer to the source and lower concentrations further away.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] These gradients signal cells' ultimate roles, such as nerve, skin cell, or connective tissue.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] The engineered organizer cells were also fitted with a chemical switch that enabled the researchers to turn the delivery of cellular instructions on and off, as well as a 'suicide switch' for eliminating the cells when needed.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] SOs carry spatial and biochemical information, allowing considerable discretion in organoid formation.
[src:stem-cell-biology/stem-cell] In August 2021, researchers in the Princess Margaret Cancer Centre at the University Health Network published their discovery of a dormancy mechanism in key stem cells which could help develop cancer treatments in the future.
